<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="RUT" stage="Final" version="A">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2013-09-22 02:38:03Z" when="2013-09-22 02:38:03Z" stage="Draft">first draft by Max Jacob in 2001; revised by Chuck 2007 and 2011 with reference to HCE, NLT, Hubbard (TW); Hebrew notes added from HCE (HCE worked with Hubbard's commentary (TW), Campbell in Anchor Bible series, Sasson, Megillah Ruth, Ronald Hals, The Theology of the Book of Ruth, H. H. Rowley, The Servant of the Lord, 'The marriage of Ruth'. Marge Crofts checked exegesis of HCE; Kupang Advisor Check with Mis, Oma, Helena, AT, Johnny 5-12 Nov 2012; Exegetical questions from Catherine Rountree July 2013; Consultant Check in Kupang, UBB 22-23 Aug 2013</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-02-24 10:31:19Z" when="2014-02-24 10:31:19Z" stage="Consult">Consultant Check: 22-23 August 2013 at UBB in Kupang; Consultant: Catherine Rountree, approved; Report: Kupang RUT report-CEG-1.pdf, followed by emails copied to Director.</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-12-19 04:26:12Z" when="2014-12-19 04:26:12Z" stage="Rev">smoothing read thru for Kupang mini-Bible done at UBB with Chuck, Oma Ora and Rina Fernandes.</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Rut</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Rut pung Carita<bt>Ruth's Story</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Elimelek dong pinda dari kampong Betlehem di tana Isra'el, pi tana Moab<bt>Elimelek (coll-pl) move from the village of Betlehem in the land of Isra'el, to the land of Moab</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-2" />Dolu-dolu, waktu balóm ada raja di tana Isra'el, tukang putus parkara yang masi ator sang orang Isra'el dong.<bt>Long ago, when there was not yet a king in the land of Isra'el, dispute settlers were the ones who still arranged things for the people of Isra'el.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Itu waktu, ada satu orang nama Elimelek. Dia tu, dari fam Efrata, dari kampong Betlehem di da'era Yahuda. Dia pung bini, nama Na'omi.<bt>At that time there was a man named Elimelek. He was from the Efrata clan/family, from the village of Betlehem in the region of Yahuda. His wife was named Na'omi.</bt><note reference="1:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Elimelek</span> ada pung arti bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan tu, Raja&gt;&gt;. Nama <span class="Italic">Na'omi</span> ada pung arti bilang, &lt;&lt;yang hati manis&gt;&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Elimelek</span> means, &lt;&lt;God is King&gt;&gt;. The name <span class="Italic">Na'omi</span> means “sweet-livered one”.</bt></note>Dong pung ana laki-laki dua orang, nama Mahlon deng Kilyon.<bt>They had two sons, named Mahlon and Kilyon. [DISCOURSE: background-foreground; EXEG: “before there were kings” is what was implied to the original audience by the phrase “when the judges ruled” (TEV, CEV, TH) Note also that the whole book of Ruth is to set the stage for the leadership of the Davidic monarchy (see 4:21-22); KT: note that these “judges” should not evoke legal specialists in modern courtrooms, but rather respected community leaders as in the notes below (arbitrators, legal counselors, settlers of disputes, givers of advice, fixers. The modern word "judge" calls up a very different set of images -- educated, part of a legal system, robes, courtroom, lawyers, police, concerned with crime and land rights, none of which have parallels in Palestine of Ruth's time. These were more on the order of influential local people of all kinds). On “Ephrathites” as a clan name, see Hubbard and TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Is this your key term"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) Is this your key term for "judge" in O.T?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) Yes. If you look at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cr) Yes. If you look at the stories in Da Local Leada Guys, what they actually did included waging war, hellraising, assassination, and a bunch of other unjudgely things. We're talking Ehud and Abimelech and Samson. Some of them had a wider sphere of influence than others. The common thread is that they were the highest authority you could call on for help at the time. Under the monarchy things got somewhat more organized, but it's still not clear whether the English title of "judge" would have been appropriate for anybody, even Solomon. We worked through that one on the New Testament, because there are reference to the "judges" and cross references to the book.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shfot hashoftim (inf + acc): judge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">shfot hashoftim (inf + acc): judge in the sense of arbitrators, legal counselors, settlers of disputes, givers of advice, fixers. The modern word "judge" calls up a very different set of images -- educated, part of a legal system, robes, courtroom, lawyers, police, concerned with crime and land rights, none of which have parallels in Palestine of Ruthʔs time. These were more on the order of influential local people of all kinds: the nice people like the Richard Smarts and the Robinsons, and also the less reputable ones like the  Larry Mehaus and the Charlie Stevenses.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00951c.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Itu waktu, ada musim lapar yang hebat di da'era Yahuda. Andia ko Elimelek dong jalan kasi tenga dong pung kampong sandiri, ko pi tenga manumpang di tana Moab, di kali Yarden pung sablá matahari nae.<bt>At that time there was a severe famine in the region of Yahuda. That is why Elimelek (coll-pl) went leaving their own village to live temporarily in the land of Moab, on the eastern side of the Yarden river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəfowT hasshofTiym: Maybe the famine was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">shəfowT hasshofTiym: Maybe the famine was because the judges hadn't done a very competent job. It could be an objective genitive-like relation, putting responsibility on the judges. The rabbinical scholars in general want there to be a reason for everything that happens, and misfortune is invariably a result of sin. Possibly Eglon was king in Moab.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕav: famine (natural, not the results"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">raʕav: famine (natural, not the results of mismanagement).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lagur (gwr inf): live as a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lagur (gwr inf): live as a foreigner in someone else's land, with no property rights or expectation of permanence. Used frequently of the patriarchs settling temporarily where the grazing was good.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bisde moʔav: in the fields (territory)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">bisde moʔav: in the fields (territory) of Moab, probably the high plateau area east of the Jordan, higher than the Judean hill country but fairly flat. "Fields" might also be part of the agricultural context.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔefratiym: Efrat people. UBS “(1) this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔefratiym: Efrat people. UBS “(1) this is merely a designation of the inhabitants of the country around Bethlehem;  (2) the phrase identifies "Ephrathah" with Bethlehem Micah 5.1 in the Hebrew text.(compare Micah 5.2); that is to say, "the Ephrathites" is only another way of talking about the inhabitants of Bethlehem itself; and (3) the phrase designates a clan of Judah which lived in Bethlehem. Since there is no special evidence for the first solution, and since the second solution appears to be a feature of later history, the third solution is probably to be preferred.”</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ma di sana, Elimelek mati, kasi tenga dia pung bini-ana dong sandiri.<bt>But [while] there, Elimelek died, leaving his wife-children on their own/alone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisshaʔer (nif): she stayed there, remained,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tisshaʔer (nif): she stayed there, remained, was bereaved. Not the usual word for staying or dwelling; she was left alone as a widow with no resources for getting back home. Happens here in the Islands sometimes too.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Waktu ana dong su bésar datang, dong kawin ame bini dari orang Moab dong. Mahlon kawin ame satu parampuan, nama Rut. Kilyon kawin ame satu parampuan, nama Orpa. Ma waktu dong su tenga manumpang di situ kira-kira sapulu taon,<bt>When the two children grew up, they married wives from the Moab people. Mahlon married a woman named Rut. Kilyon married a woman named Orpa. But when they had lived there (temporarily, not settled permanently) for about ten years, [EXEG: Hebrew is ambiguous: 1) married upon arrival and died after 10 years, or 2) after staying there awhile, they married toward the end of ten years and then died. CEV, NLT and Hubbard favour #1 to build expectation for children, but higher context and clues later in book allow for #2 as well.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayisʔu (nsʔ narr): they married, they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vayisʔu (nsʔ narr): they married, they took wives (not as common as yiqachu "they took").</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lahem: for themselves; they had no"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lahem: for themselves; they had no father to deal with bride price and dowry, so they did their own negotiations</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hebrew has chiasm on the names"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">Hebrew has chiasm on the names a b : b a : UBS. Makes more sense in Pidgin to match them a b : a' b'.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeshvuw: they stayed there. Coming at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vayyeshvuw: they stayed there. Coming at the end of the verse, it may be ambiguous; it could mean that the whole family including daughters-in-law stayed together ten years before the sons died, or less likely, it could mean that the Elimelek family was there ten years before the sons died, in which case the marriages could have taken place toward the end of the ten years.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Na'omi pung ana laki-laki dua orang, andia Mahlon deng Kilyon, mati ju. Dong mati kasi tenga dong pung mama sandiri--sonde ada pung laki, sonde ada pung ana, deng sonde ada pung cucu.<bt>Na'omi's two sons, that is Mahlon and Kilyon, also died. They died leaving their mother on her own--without a husband, without children, and without grandchildren. [EXEG: Heb: progeny; HCE, no heirs sets stage for the whole book.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəladeyha: her progeny. Although her boys"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yəladeyha: her progeny. Although her boys were grown, they were her offspring, her babies, her kids.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00955c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Did anyone on the translation">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) Did anyone on the translation team wonder why there is no statement about grandchildren also being zero?  Is it OK that that fact comes to light only later? It is background information.</Message>
      </Annotation>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) I think you're right about">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cr) I think you're right about putting it in here. There weren't grandsons for a different reason than there weren't any sons; the sons had died prematurely, but they hadn't had any sons of their own before they died. If they had, the inheritance would have been taken care of. The levirate marriage system and its ties to the land are the key piece of implicit information that one needs in order to make sense of the whole book. Since that kind of thing is understandable here, but not part of the legal system as such, we had better bring it out every place it fits. But nobody brought it up, because Ruth is still a neat story whether you know the rationale behind it or not.</Message>
      </Annotation>
    </p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Na'omi deng Rut kambali pi Betlehem<bt>Na'omi and Rut return to Betlehem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Waktu Na'omi masi tenga di tana Moab, dia dapa dengar bilang, TUHAN ada inga Dia pung orang di da'era Yahuda, ais su ada makanan di sana lai. Andia ko Na'omi deng dia pung ana mantu dua orang manyimpan ko mau kasi tenga tana Moab ko kambali pi dia pung da'era sandiri.<bt>When Na'omi was still living in the land of Mo'ab, she heard/got news that GOD had remembered His people in the region of Yahuda, and now there was food there again. That is why Na'omi and her two daughters-in-law packed up to leave the land of Moab to return to her own region. [EXEG: vs. 6 as preparation, NLT, Hubbard, TB2.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalloteyha: her daughta-in-laws. NOT daughters-in-law [that's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">kalloteyha: her daughta-in-laws. NOT daughters-in-law [that's the English inflection pattern for compounds, not Pidgin]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paqad: remember for good = be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">paqad: remember for good = be gracious, have mercy</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais dong tiga jalan kasi tenga mamatua pung ruma di tana Moab, iko jalan yang pulang pi da'era Yahuda.<bt>Then the three of them left/abandoned the old lady's [term of respect] house in the land of Moab, following the road that returned/went home to the region of Yahuda.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="telakhnah (hlk narr): they travelled by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">telakhnah (hlk narr): they travelled by the road to go back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔerets: land of Judah (where Naʕomi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔerets: land of Judah (where Naʕomi had property rights) - not just the region</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ma waktu dong ada jalan, Na'omi kasi tau dia pung ana mantu dua orang tu bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Lebe bae bosong dua pulang pi bosong pung mama dong sa. Te bosong su kasi tunju hati bae sang beta pung ana yang su mati dong, deng beta ju. Andia ko beta minta ko TUHAN Allah ju kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang bosong dua.<bt>But while they were travelling, Na'omi told her two daughters-in-law saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! It would be better for the two of you to go home to your own mothers. Cuz (elaboration) you have shown your good livers (=goodness, kindness, generosity) to my children who have died, and also to me. Therefore I ask LORD God to also show His good liver to the two of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lekhnah (hlk imperv pl): go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lekhnah (hlk imperv pl): go</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shovnah (shwb imperv pl): return"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">shovnah (shwb imperv pl): return</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔishshah: each of you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔishshah: each of you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yʕs chesed (rabbis treat it as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yʕs chesed (rabbis treat it as jussive): may he act with solidarity to the community, be faithful. This is the word usually used for sticking with a covenant agreement; "stay tight" is more like a personal commitment. It's one of the most heavily loaded words in the Hebrew Bible. Translations like "mercy" and "lovingkindness" miss the convenant rationale that underlies it - God has committed himself to a relationship with us, and thatʔs why he treats us well, and expects us to live up to our part of the commitment. JR: can be read as an imperfect; "he will deal with you faithfully"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəsiytem: you (fem pl) did. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʕəsiytem: you (fem pl) did. The thing they did was to behave consistently the way the covenant said toward their husbands and mother-in-law, and she wants God to do the same for them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hammetiym (mwt partcpl pl): the deceased"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hammetiym (mwt partcpl pl): the deceased ones. Unusual way of putting it; highlights that all obligations are cancelled. Or maybe she doesnʔt want to say their names.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Biar ko Dia ju kasi bosong dua, laki baru yang pung hati bae, ko bosong bisa idop aman sa.&gt;&gt; Ais mamatua paló-ciom dong dua, ju dong manangis kuat-kuat.<bt>May He also give the two of you new husbands who are good livered, so you can live in safety/security.&gt;&gt; Then the old lady hugged-kissed the two of them, and they wept strongly/loudly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitten (jussive): may he give, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yitten (jussive): may he give, he will give</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mtseʔna (mtsʔ imperv): find"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">mtseʔna (mtsʔ imperv): find</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mnuchah: resting place, secure place, like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">mnuchah: resting place, secure place, like mnoach in 3:1. A home with a husband, a place where they will have the security of an established home.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiyshah: her husband"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔiyshah: her husband</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishshaq (nshq narr): she kissed (this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tishshaq (nshq narr): she kissed (this is a goodbye kiss)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisseʔnah (nsʔ fem pl): they lifted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tisseʔnah (nsʔ fem pl): they lifted up their voice. This could be just Ruth and Orpah, while Naʕomi is arguing rationally</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ma dong dua bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde, mama! Botong mau iko deng mama, ko idop sama-sama di mama pung orang dong sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the two of them said, &lt;&lt;No, mother! We-exc are going to accompany you, to live together with your people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ma Na'omi manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana sayang dong, é! Pulang su! Dia pung guna apa, kalo bosong iko sang beta? Te beta ni su tua, deng sonde bisa barana ame ana laki-laki lai yang bisa jadi bosong pung laki kalo dong su bésar datang. Sonde mungkin, to?<bt>But Na'omi responded saying, &lt;&lt;Dear children! Just go on home! What use is it if you accompany me? Cuz (elaboration) I am already old, and am not capable of giving birth to other sons who can become your husbands when they grow up. That's not likely, right [+tag question, expecting assent]?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) That's my question, too."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) That's my question, too.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) SK calls her daughters-in-law by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cr) SK calls her daughters-in-law by name, not "girl" or "daughta," though either would be understood.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bnotay: my daughtas. (In Pidgin would"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">bnotay: my daughtas. (In Pidgin would a woman address her daughter-in-law as "daughta"? "girl"?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʕod-li: is there still in/with me?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">haʕod-li: is there still in/with me? Do I still have?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəmeʕay: in my womb - The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">bəmeʕay: in my womb - The levirate, keeping a family line going and keeping property in the family line by passing the wife of a deceased person to a brother, and in some cases a cousin or even the father-in-law (as with Judah, also in Assyrian law). Here the reference to the levirate would involve a widow marrying a relative of her deceased husband, have a boy, betroth that boy to a widowed daughter-in-law, thereby preserving the land rights of her first husbandʔs family line</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Biar bosong dua ni sama ke beta pung ana sandiri, ma lebe bae bosong pulang sa. Te beta su tua ni, jadi bosong jang kira beta bisa kawin ulang lai. Beta sandiri sonde harap bagitu. Andekata ini malam ju, beta jadi kawin, tarús dapa ana laki-laki lai, na, bosong pung pikir karmana?<bt>Even though the two of you are like my own children, nevertheless it would be better if you just go home. Cuz (elaboration) with me old like this, you should not think I can marry again. I myself am not hoping like that. If perchance [+hypothetical] tonight it worked out for me to marry, then get other sons, na, what are you thinking?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chance fo get one guy tonite,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">chance fo get one guy tonite, ...</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lekhna: go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lekhna: go</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiqwah: hope"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tiqwah: hope</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayeyti ... lʔish: I would belong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hayeyti ... lʔish: I would belong to a man - sexually explicit, doesnʔt necessarily imply or exclude marriage</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Bosong kira bosong mau tunggu itu ana dong bésar datang, ais kawin ame sang dong? Jang sampe bosong sonde tahan, ais kawin dolu deng orang laen. Susa, to? Ma beta pung susa lebe pait dari bosong pung susa, te beta rasa ke TUHAN Allah sandiri yang maen tampeleng sang beta. Jadi lebe bae bosong jang iko sang beta lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Do you think you are going to wait for those children to grow up, then marry them? May it not be that you are not able to endure, and so marry first with someone else. It's hard/difficult, right? But my difficulty is more bitter than your-pl difficulty, cuz (elaboration) I feel as if the LORD God himself is the one who has been slapping/punishing me. So (consequently), it would be better if you do not follow/accompany me anymore.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: TN discusses ambiguity of ‘No’. We've shifted it to make it a transition between the first part of the verse and the second part. “(No,) that would be unlikely/difficult.” Last clause reinforcing what Hubbard calls the climax. Aspect from context, not in conflict with Heb perfect “has been raised against me”. Note TB (incorrectly) only implies that punishment is threatened, but hasn't actually happened.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisabbernah (sbr piʕel): you would wait,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tisabbernah (sbr piʕel): you would wait, hope</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teʕagenah (nif): keep yourselves withdrawn, out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">teʕagenah (nif): keep yourselves withdrawn, out of the running for marriage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lviltiy: so that not, so as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lviltiy: so that not, so as not to get a husband</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mar (mrr): it is much more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">mar (mrr): it is much more bitter, hard to cope with, difficult for me than for you. UBS suggests "because the Lord has turned against me, I am terribly sorry for you," which doesnʔt quite mesh with mikem "more sorry than you are."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatsʔah bi yad-yʔ (ntsʔ): because the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yatsʔah bi yad-yʔ (ntsʔ): because the hand of the Lord goes out against me, the Lord has hit me, turned against me.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00956c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Tarús dong tiga manangis makarareu ulang lai. Ais Orpa ciom ame dia pung mama mantu, ju pamit sang dia, ais pulang kambali. Ma Rut paló kuat-kuat sang dia pung mama mantu.<bt>Then the three of them wept in grief again. Then2 Orpa kissed her mother-in-law, took her leave from her, and then returned home. But Rut kept hugging/clinging to her mother-in-law. [EXEG: strong agreement among commentaries that Orpah's kiss implies good-by and leaving.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tissenah (nsʔ): they lifted up their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tissenah (nsʔ): they lifted up their voices. Again, the younger women seem to be crying, while Naomi keeps her head.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisshaq: she kissed (kissed her bood-bye"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tisshaq: she kissed (kissed her bood-bye and left, implicit)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmotah: her mother-in-law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">chəmotah: her mother-in-law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="davqah: clung to her, a rather"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">davqah: clung to her, a rather strong action. Orpah returning and Ruth clinging are simultaneous, indicated by the chiasm and imperfective-perfective sequence (Hubbard).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Na'omi kasi tau sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Lia sa! Orpa su pulang pi dia pung orang deng dia pung barang songgo-songgo dong. Akurang ko lu sonde pulang pi sama-sama deng dia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Na'omi told her saying, &lt;&lt;Have a look! Orpa has gone home to her people and her worship things. Why is it that you are not going back together with her?&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “her gods”, (although Hubbard notes authorities who claim there was only Chemosh worshipped in Moab). This is a challenge to translate directly in Kupang and all daughter lgs, and at best would be confusing, ambiguous, and skew the focus. Works better to go indirect and focus on the act of traditional worship, which implies the beings behind it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yvimtekh: your husbandʔs brotherʔs wife"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yvimtekh: your husbandʔs brotherʔs wife</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəloheyah: her gods, her god. Chemosh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔəloheyah: her gods, her god. Chemosh was the only god mentioned for Moab. Hubbard: Despite the Hebrew plural (ʔé|lOheyhA, lit. "her gods"), the reference is surely to the Moabite god Chemosh (hence, her god).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ma Rut manyao bilang,<bt>But Rut responded saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Jang mara, ma mama jang suru beta pulang.<bt>&lt;&lt;Don't be angry/I'm sorry, but mother should not order me to return home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng mama jang paksa ko beta jalan kasi tenga mama sandiri.<bt>And mother should not force for me to abandon you [to be] alone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te beta mau makaditi tarús deng mama.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I am going to/intend to keep sticking to you. [NOTE: like glue. Term used for a child who hangs on apron strings, or a tag-along.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mama pi mana, na, beta pi sana ju.<bt>Wherever mother goes, na, I'm going there too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mama tenga di mana, na, beta tenga di situ ju.<bt>Wherever mother lives, na, I'm going to live there too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mama pung orang dong nanti jadi beta pung orang ju.<bt>Mother's people will become my people too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng mama pung Tuhan Allah nanti jadi beta pung Tuhan Allah ju.<bt>And mother's Lord God will become my Lord God too.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Weaeva you like stay, I goin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">Weaeva you like stay, I goin stay dea too.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tifgəʕi-vi (pgʕ imperf): do not entreat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tifgəʕi-vi (pgʕ imperf): do not entreat me. TWOT The third way the verb is used is in the context of making intercession (1) to man (Ruth 1:16, "entreat me not," i.e. "donʔt press me to leave you," and Gen 23:8, "entreat for me to Ephron," i.e. "put pressure on, use your influence"); (2) to God (Jer 7:16, "donʔt make intercession to me"; also Jer 27:18; Job 21:15).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʕazvekh: to leave you, let you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lʕazvekh: to leave you, let you go. Dvq ʕzb is what you get in Genesis, stick to the wife, leave the parents.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taliyniy (lwn): you spend the night"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">taliyniy (lwn): you spend the night somewhere, lodge somewhere, live somewhere</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕammekh ʕammiy: answers to Orpahʔs &quot;people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʕammekh ʕammiy: answers to Orpahʔs "people and god", in verbless clauses where she says she is going to break with her culture and adopt Naomiʔs</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Nanti mama mati di mana, na, beta mati di situ ju.<bt>Wherever mother later dies, na, I will die there too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dong kubur mama di mana, na, dong kubur sang beta di mama pung rebis ju.<bt>Wherever they bury mother, na, they will bury me at your side/ribs too. [NOTE: natural collocation. they talk this way.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar ko TUHAN hukum sang beta,<bt>May the LORD punish me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kalo beta tapisa dari mama.<bt>if I separate from mother.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te mati ju sonde bisa kasi pisa kotong dua na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) death cannot separate the two of us-inc [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Check personification.] [EXEG: discuss with team: add “Be sumpa” ? To indicate genre? Commentators agree that the Hebrew phrasing is an oath.] [EXEG: this is an interesting and tricky one. NRSV is the closest to the Heb. in BART “May the LORD do thus and so to me, and more as well, if even death parts me from you!” CEV is similar, “May the LORD punish me if we are ever separated, even by death!” (One possible rephrase here is ‘not even death can separate us’). NIV and NLT add a ‘but’ contrast which I don't find in the Heb. which changes the polarity. NIV “May the LORD deal with me, be it ever so severely, if anything but death separates you and me.” NLT1/NLT2 “May the LORD punish me severely if I allow anything but death to separate us!” So there seem to be two polar opposite expressions here, which actually seem to mean the same thing if you take them as hyperbole, which is how we've phrased it in the Kupang. Note, given the structure of 17a here, this rendering is the only one that makes sense in this context. The NIV strategy does not. See also discussion of disagreements in TN. Hubbard disagrees with NIV interpretation from contextual clues of 17a.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeqqaver (qbr nif): I will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔeqqaver (qbr nif): I will be buried</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoSiyf (ySp hif imperf): may he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yoSiyf (ySp hif imperf): may he do more. She is taking this change with a solemn oath. Hubbard: To confirm the deadly seriousness of her intentions, Ruth swore an oath in Yahwehʔs name (Thus may Yahweh do to me and more so)... As for the condition, one must ask whether the emphatic position of death  conveys the sense "only death/anything but death" or "even death."  While the oath formula itself favors the former, the immediate context favors the latter... If Ruth says, "I will be buried where you are buried" (v. 17a), clearly implying common burial with Naomi, it hardly makes sense for her to add, "Only death will separate us" (v. 17b). In sum, the condition was if even death  [Hebrew emphatic] itself separates me from you.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafriyd (prd hif imperf): death causes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yafriyd (prd hif imperf): death causes a separation between me and you.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Jadi waktu Na'omi lia kalo Rut su tanam kaki ko mau iko sang dia, dia sonde omong banya lai.<bt>So (consequently) when Na'omi saw that Rut had planted her feet to accompany her, she didn't say much anymore. (= had nothing else to say).  [NOTE to daughter translations: /kalo/ here is complementizer ‘that’, not conditional ‘if’. Idiom: banya is not productive = didn't say anything.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ki-mitʔametseh (ʔmts hitp): that Ruth took"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ki-mitʔametseh (ʔmts hitp): that Ruth took courage, was strong; JR had made up her mind.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalekhet (hlk inf): to go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">lalekhet (hlk inf): to go</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="techdal: stop doing something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">techdal: stop doing something</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais dong dua jalan tarús, sampe di kampong Betlehem.<bt>Then the two of them continued walking/their journey, arriving in the village of Betlehem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu itu dua parampuan su sampe di sana, samua orang taheran-heran tagal dong. Parampuan dari itu kampong dong batanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Batúl, ko? Ini mama Omi, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>When the two women arrived there, everyone was surprised/amazed because of them. The women of that village asked each other saying, &lt;&lt;Is it true? Is this mother Omi, [+tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boʔanah (bwʔ inf fem pl): arrive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">boʔanah (bwʔ inf fem pl): arrive</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tehom (hwm nif): they were in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tehom (hwm nif): they were in a stir; got excited</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔmarnah (ʔmr imperf fem pl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">toʔmarnah (ʔmr imperf fem pl): the women said</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00959c.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ma Na'omi kasi tau sang dong bilang,<bt>But Na'omi told them saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Bagini! Bosong jang pange beta <span class="Italic">Na'omi</span> lai,<bt>&lt;&lt;It's like this! You-pl should not call me <span class="Italic">Na'omi</span> anymore,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te itu dia pung arti bilang, &lt;yang hati manis&gt;.<bt>cuz (elaboration) that means, &lt;sweet-livered one&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Good....implied info so necessary to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) Good....implied info so necessary to make this make sense.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lebe bae bosong pange beta <span class="Italic">Mara,</span><bt>It would be better to call me Mara,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te itu dia pung arti bilang, &lt;yang hati pait&gt;.<bt>cuz (elaboration) that means, &lt;bitter-livered one&gt;.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te Tuhan yang Paling Kuasa su bekin beta pung idop jadi talalu pait.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the Almighty God has made my life too bitter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəʕam: be pleasant, be agreeable, gratifying,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">nəʕam: be pleasant, be agreeable, gratifying, taste good, be dear to someone (also verse 21)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maraʔ: sounds kinda like &quot;bitter&quot; (marah)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">maraʔ: sounds kinda like "bitter" (marah)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hemar (mrr hif): he has made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hemar (mrr hif): he has made things bitter, sad for me. It's a picture word; bile from an animal's gall bladder is bitter, and some plants taste bitter.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʔod: extremely"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">məʔod: extremely</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shadday: the Almighty. NET The divine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">shadday: the Almighty. NET The divine name translated Sovereign One is shadday (“Shaddai”). Shaddai (or El Shaddai) is the sovereign king/judge of the world who grants life/blesses and kills/judges. In the Book of Genesis he blesses the patriarchs with fertility and promises numerous descendants. Outside Genesis he both blesses/protects and takes away life/happiness.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />Dolu, waktu beta kaluar dari sini,<bt>Long ago, when I left here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">beta langkáp, te beta ada pung laki deng beta ada pung ana dua.<bt>I was complete, cuz (elaboration) I had a husband and two children.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ma sakarang Tuhan bawa pulang sang beta,<bt>But now God2 has brought me home,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kosong-kosong sa.<bt>completely empty/with nothing at all.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Jadi, akurang ko bosong pange sang beta &lt;Na'omi&gt;,<bt>So (consequently), why do you call me &lt;Na'omi&gt;,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kalo TUHAN ada maen tampeleng sang beta?<bt>if the LORD is slapping/punishing me?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te Dia yang Paling Kuasa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is the Almighty.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Deng Dia yang bekin susa sang beta na!&gt;&gt;<bt>And He is the one who is causing me difficulty [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mleʔah: full"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">mleʔah: full</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reyqam: empty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">reyqam: empty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həshivani (hif perf): he brought me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">həshivani (hif perf): he brought me back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəʕomi: be pleasant, be agreeable, gratifying,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">nəʕomi: be pleasant, be agreeable, gratifying, taste good, be dear to someone</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕanah: he answers me? he gives"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʕanah: he answers me? he gives me a hard time? he testifies against me (JR sounds like Job)? RS: YHWH and Shadday are fronted, sounding like an accusation.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heraʕ (rʕʕ hif): do evil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">heraʕ (rʕʕ hif): do evil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Itu dia pung carita waktu Na'omi pulang dari tana Moab deng dia pung ana mantu Rut, yang orang Moab tu. Dong dua sampe di Betlehem, pas deng musim koru jagong rote.<bt>That was the story when Na'omi returned home from the land of Moab with her daughter-in-law Rut, the Moab person. The two of them arrived in Betlehem just at the time of harvesting sorghum/barley. [NOTE: the two crops are not distinguished here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hasshavah: article as relative pronoun, who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hasshavah: article as relative pronoun, who returned</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bitchillat (chll): at the beginning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">bitchillat (chll): at the beginning</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qətsiyr: harvest. Naomi's land has nothing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">qətsiyr: harvest. Naomi's land has nothing to harvest, so they are forced to glean.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəʕorim: barley. Poor people's food, costs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">shəʕorim: barley. Poor people's food, costs less than wheat. On the coast in Palestine the harvest is in March or April, but in May up country where Bethlehem is located. It comes in a month earlier than the wheat.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rut karjá di Bo'as pung kabón<bt>Rut works in Bo'as' garden/field</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Di Betlehem ada satu orang kaya, nama Bo'as. Dia bakelu deng Elimelek, andia Na'omi pung laki yang su mati. Jadi kasi orang di situ dong, Bo'as tu, sama ke Na'omi pung ipar satu.<bt>In Betlehem there was a rich person, named Bo'as. He was related to Elimelek, that is Na'omi's husband who had died. So (consequently) to the people there, this Bo'as was a cross-sex in-law to Na'omi. [EXEG: 2 Hebrew adjs are both carried by implications of “orang kaya” (rich person) Overall packaging of background info like HCE. LEX: konyadu = male-male; ipar = cross gender]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="modaʕ (qereʔ, from ydʕ), məyuddaʕ (ktiv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">modaʕ (qereʔ, from ydʕ), məyuddaʕ (ktiv): kinsman, relative, one who is known (as family)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiyshah: her husband"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔiyshah: her husband</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gibbor: mighty man, prominent. 2 separate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">gibbor: mighty man, prominent. 2 separate adjectives</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chayil: power, wealth, strength, army; competence;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">chayil: power, wealth, strength, army; competence; someone to be reckoned with.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishpachat: clan, lineage - key to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">mishpachat: clan, lineage - key to all the rest of the story, which involves perpetuation of Elimelek's lineage and property rights as a framework for Ruth's personal story. It also defines the boundaries for blood vengeance feuds. The laws are more detailed, trying to curb vengeance, but the clan would often take it into its own hands. A city of refuge offered neutral territory, and allowed for judicial process if a crime were deliberate.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Satu kali, itu parampuan asing orang Moab, andia Rut, pi dia pung mama mantu ko minta bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama, é! Bisa ko, beta pi kabón dong ko pili ame jagong rote sisa yang jato di balakang orang karjá dong? [Te Tuhan pung Atoran ada tulis bilang kasi tenga orang miskin bekin bagitu.]<bt>One time, that foreign Moabite woman, that is Rut, went to her mother-in-law to request saying, &lt;&lt;Mama, é! May I go to the fields to retrieve the extra/leftover barley/sorghum which falls behind the workers? [Cuz (elaboration) God's Regulations write that they should allow poor people to do that.] [EXEG: implicit - explicit “because God2's Rules say that is good” covers something that every Jew of that time understood, but which always has to be explained to audiences today. UBS "According to the law of the Hebrews, strangers, widows, orphans, and other poor people had the right to collect the ears of grain which had fallen from the hands of the reapers and were left behind in the field." TH, HCE. See cf. NOTE: UNSs found this bit critical to understanding what was going on here—otherwise they would assume either she was stealing, or else whe was formally hired as a worker, neither of which is correct.] [LEX choice: what I gloss as &lt;retrieve&gt; is a local concept of picking something up that has fallen, often inadvertently fallen unnoticed.]</bt><note reference="2:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kapala Agama dong pung Atoran 19:9-10, Carita Ulang so'al Jalan Idop 24:19, 25:5-6</note>Jang sampe ada orang yang mau kasi tunju dia pung hati bae sang beta bagitu. Bisa, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>Perhaps there is someone who wants to show their good liver (goodness, kindness, generosity) to me in that way. May I?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Mamatua manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae ju. Pi su.&gt;&gt;<bt>The old [respected] lady responded saying, &lt;&lt;That's good. Go on.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) I'm going to write a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) I'm going to write a paper with percentages of languages that never use a possessive pronoun with a vocative.  I'd guess it is very high.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) How Starlight talk to Jenna?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cr) How Starlight talk to Jenna? "My boy" as a term of address isn't all that rare, but "my girl' or "my daughta" in direct address is rare. SK uses proper name or nothing, and she has a bunch of daughters-in-law.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hammoʔəviyyah: the Moab woman. Hebrew repeats"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hammoʔəviyyah: the Moab woman. Hebrew repeats this kind of information all over the place, and though here it may be a reminder that Ruth is a foreigner, it may sound redundant and not be needed here.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔelkhah-naʔ (hlk imperf): I will go."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔelkhah-naʔ (hlk imperf): I will go. The naʔ is deprecative, indicating that Ruth is proposing to do something and wants permission, and Naʕomi gives her permission to do it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaʕəlaqotah (piʕel): I will gather up."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vaʕəlaqotah (piʕel): I will gather up. This is a technical term for the legal right poor people had, to pick up any extra grain, mentioned in the Law, hence "cuz God's Rules say az good" covers something that every Jew of that time understood, but which always has to be explained to a Pidgin speaker. UBS "According to the law of the Hebrews, strangers, widows, orphans, and other poor people had the right to collect the ears of grain which had fallen from the hands of the reapers and were left behind in the field."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bashibbolim (shibbolet): bunches, ears"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">bashibbolim (shibbolet): bunches, ears</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔachar: behind, after whoever ..."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔachar: behind, after whoever ...</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔemtsaʔ-chen bʕeynayw: the one in whose"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">ʔemtsaʔ-chen bʕeynayw: the one in whose eyes I find favor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biti: my daughter. What would an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">biti: my daughter. What would an older Local woman use when she talks to the widow of her deceased son, and they both respect each other and are good friends? daughta-in-law? girl? "Daughta" is OK, but "My daughta" sounds strange.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Rut pi satu kabón ko pili ame jagong rote yang orang karjá dong sonde ame waktu dong ada koru. Tau-tau te itu kabón tu, andia Bo'as pung tana milik. Dia yang bakelu deng Elimelek, andia Rut pung bapa mantu yang su mati.<bt>Then Rut went to a field to retrieve barley/sorghum which the workers had not taken while they were picking/harvesting. It turned out that field was owned by Bo'as. He is the one who was related to Elimelek, that is Rut's father-in-law who had died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattelekh vattavoʔ: You get a cover"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vattelekh vattavoʔ: You get a cover statement, followed by detail statements in sequence that may go back before the cover statement. Does Pidgin?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tlaqqeT (lqT piʕel): she gathered up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">tlaqqeT (lqT piʕel): she gathered up</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqqotsriym: the ones doing the harvesting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">haqqotsriym: the ones doing the harvesting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqer (qrh): it befell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vayyiqer (qrh): it befell</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqreha (qrh): happening, accident, result; by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">miqreha (qrh): happening, accident, result; by chance. She didn't go to Boaz's field consciously, but just picked one that looked like they wouldn't mind her picking up the extra grain and started doing it. God knew, but she didn't.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chelqat: field, that very field. TWOT:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">chelqat: field, that very field. TWOT: The verb is commonly used of parcelling out shares (RSV "allotments") of land (Num 26:53), whether by lot (Num 26:53), inheritance (Prov 17:2), or other forms of division (Prov 29:24).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Naa. Waktu Rut ada pili ame jagong rote tu, takuju sa, tuan kabón, andia Bo'as, muncul datang dari kampong ko lia dia pung orang karjá dong. Dia togor sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Saloom! Biar ko TUHAN Allah jaga bae-bae sang bosong!&gt;&gt;<bt>Now... [Kupang rhetorical device] When Rut was retrieving barley/sorghum, suddenly the owner of the field, that is Bo'as, showed up from the village to see his workers. He greeted them saying, &lt;&lt;Saloom! May the LORD God wathc over you carefully!&gt;&gt; [NOTE: The Hebrew &lt;Saloom!&gt; is used widely by Christians across Indonesia as a greeting, to contrast with the Arabic &lt;Salamu alekhum!&gt; that Muslims use to publicly identify their religious affiliation.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Saloom, bapa! Biar ko TUHAN Allah kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang bapa ju!&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded saying, &lt;&lt;Saloom, father/sir! May the LORD God show His good liver to you also!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəhinneh: surprise, significance of the present"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">vəhinneh: surprise, significance of the present situation. Hubbard: The particle hinnEh  also underscores the presence of the person to which it refers in the same locale and at the same time as the narrator. JR: Ruth may have been waiting for Boaz to show up so she could get permission, because as a relative of her husband's he was likely to favor her. You don't just show up and start gleaning.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʔ (participle for simultaneous? perfect for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">baʔ (participle for simultaneous? perfect for Boaz coming in after Ruth got there?): came. Verse 7 makes it clear that Ruth had come in the morning and had been working for some time before Boas showed up.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəvarekh-kha: may the Lord bless you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">yəvarekh-kha: may the Lord bless you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00964c.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lia satu parampuan ada pili ame jagong rote, ju Bo'as tanya sang dia pung mandor bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Itu parampuan muda di situ tu, sapa pung kelu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing a woman retrieving barley/sorghum, Bo'as asked his site.supervisor saying, &lt;&lt;Awii [+surprise!] That young woman there is whose family?&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Boaz is probing to find out how Ruth fits into their social structure. How does your language do this naturally?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Teens?  I thought she'd"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cn) Teens?  I thought she'd been married for six years...</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) All it says is that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">(cr) All it says is that the boys were born in Israel, but reached marriageable age while in Moab. Naomi stayed a total of ten years in Moab, without saying how long after the boys' death she stayed. See the note on 1:4. So Ruth could have been anywhere from 14 to about 25. However, it's less likely that she could have gotten a second husband if she were at the upper end of the age range.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="UNS: one not use mandor much"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z">UNS: one not use mandor much</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕəro: his young man. It's the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">naʕəro: his young man. It's the masculine form of the same noun that Boaz uses to identify Ruth; but in the context of the workers it has the meaning "servant," possibly "servant in charge of the work crew," and, like Greek pais, doesn't really imply that he was as young as Ruth, who may have been still in her teens.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanittsav (nif ptcpl): the one put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:03Z" status="Information">hanittsav (nif ptcpl): the one put in charge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lmiy: to whom, probably in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lmiy: to whom, probably in the sense of "where does she fit in our town society?" And that's the kind of answer Boaz got. The Targum (Aramaic translation) uses that sense.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕərah: young woman, marriageable age"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">naʕərah: young woman, marriageable age</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Itu mandor kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Dia tu, orang Moab yang baru pulang sama-sama deng mama Omi dari sana.<bt>The supervisor told him saying, &lt;&lt;She is the Moab person who just came back together with mother Omi from there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hasshavah (shwb, article used as relativizer):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hasshavah (shwb, article used as relativizer): she who came back. In Pidgin, Naomi was the one who "came back," and Ruth "came" with her.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Tadi pagi dia datang sang beta ko minta bilang, &lt;Bos, é! Biar ko beta pili ame jagong rote sisa yang orang karjá dong sonde ika di situ.&gt; Ju beta manyao bilang, &lt;Neu!&gt; Jadi dia su karjá karás dari tadi pagi sampe sakarang ni. Dia cuma barenti karjá sadiki sa di itu ruma kabón.&gt;&gt;<bt>Earlier this morning she came to me to ask, saying &lt;Bos, é! Please let me retrieve leftover barley/sorghum that the workers do not bind over there.&gt; So I responded saying, &lt;OK [colloquial]!&gt; So she has been working hard from this morning until now. She has only stopped work/rested briefly in that field hut.&gt;&gt;  [EXEG: NLT/HCE]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaSafti: I will collect it, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔaSafti: I will collect it, take it away</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʕəmarim: where the sheaves of barley"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">baʕəmarim: where the sheaves of barley are. The rules for gleaning were that the gleaner had to stay behind the harvesters, so this may either be stuck in from Verse 15, or it may just point to the general part of the field where she started picking up grain. Syriac and Vulgate omit the word.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʕamod: keeps going, persists; keeps standing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">taʕamod: keeps going, persists; keeps standing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaz: from that time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔaz: from that time</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivtah (yshb inf fem): for her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shivtah (yshb inf fem): for her to sit / rest. Or is it that she hasn't wasted any time getting out of Naomi's house and going to work? The harvest doesn't last long, and it can burn, or rain can ruin it, and brigands can walk off with it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bayit: house. Makes sense to envision"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bayit: house. Makes sense to envision a small shack for shade and rest, like the one in the middle of the watercress patch at Sumida Farm on Kamehameha Highway in Pearlridge (REB). But some interpreters take it to mean that she was on her feet working all day (or all morning) until she sat down for a while before returning to her home at Naʕomi's place (CEV).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mʕat: small, short time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">mʕat: small, short time</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais Bo'as pi ba'omong deng Rut bilang, &lt;&lt;Susi! Lu ni, orang baru, jadi dengar bae-bae sang beta dolo. Biar ko lu pili ame jagong rote sisa di sini sa. Sonde usa pinda pi orang laen pung kabón. Ma lebe bae, jang jao-jao dari itu nona dong yang ada karjá kasi sang beta di sini.<bt>Then Bo'as went to speak with Rut saying, &lt;&lt;Sister! You are a new person, so (consequently) listen to me carefully now. You should retrieve the leftover barley/sorghum just from here. You don't need to move to somebody else's field. But it would be best if you don't get too far from those young women who are working for me here. [EXEG: JEG notes on Hebrew biti: Boaz would not have called her "my daughta" if he had been talking Pidgin. He might have been quite a bit older, though not necessarily. But he probably knew that she had been married, because it seems to have been common knowledge around Bethlehem, and one does not become either important or rich in such a setting without knowing what's going on. And in Verse 11 he says he knows. But where there is no great difference in age, "sista" is more appropriate in Pidgin.] [NOTE to daughter translations: find a natural vocative that works for a man addressing a woman he has not met, but make sure it is a term that leaves open a possible marriage relationship. Avoid a term that sets them into a taboo or non-marriagable relationship.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Double check JG."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cn) Double check JG.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) Fine with SK. &quot;Dass da"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cr) Fine with SK. "Dass da ony way fo talk. Oddawise she get mad if you call um someting else."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həloʔ shamaʕat: haven't you heard? you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">həloʔ shamaʕat: haven't you heard? you should understand? listen up, young lady? It's a superior talking to an inferior, giving a piece of advice.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biti: Boaz would not have called"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">biti: Boaz would not have called her "my daughta" if he had been talking Pidgin. He might have been quite a bit older, though not necessarily. But he probably knew that she had been married, because it seems to have been common knowledge around Bethlehem, and one does not become either important or rich in such a setting without knowing what's going on. And in Verse 11 he says he knows. But where there is no great difference in age, "sista" is more appropriate in Pidgin.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔacher: other"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔacher: other</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam loʔ taʕburi: also, don't pass"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">gam loʔ taʕburi: also, don't pass from this</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koh: thus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">koh: thus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tidbaqiyn: you will cling to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tidbaqiyn: you will cling to</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕərotay: my servant girls"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">naʕərotay: my servant girls</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Lia bae-bae kalo dong ada koru di mana, ais dong su lewat itu tampa, na, susi pili ame jagong rote sisa di dong pung balakang. Beta su kasi tau sang itu laki-laki dong ko jang ganggu sang lu. Ais kalo aus, na, pi minum aer di itu kumbang yang dong su isi dari parigi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Watch carefully where they are picking/harvesting, then when they have passed that place, na, sister can retrieve the leftover/extra barley/sorghum that is behind them. I have already told those men to not bother you. [NOTE: can imply sexual harrassment too.] So if you are thirsty, na, go drink water from the just that they have filled from the well.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕeynaykh ba-: your eyes on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕeynaykh ba-: your eyes on</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqtsorun: they are harvesting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yiqtsorun: they are harvesting</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2017-09-24 22:59:51Z">&gt;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halakht: you (fem) go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">halakht: you (fem) go</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwiti (tswh piʕel): I have given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tsiwwiti (tswh piʕel): I have given orders</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lbilti nagʕekh (ngʕ inf): to not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lbilti nagʕekh (ngʕ inf): to not touch you. A young, beautiful, foreigner with no protector? Don't chew her out for drinking your water?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsamit (tsmʔ): you are thirsty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tsamit (tsmʔ): you are thirsty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hakelim: the pots for water, like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hakelim: the pots for water, like the old fashioned field coolers with no insulation and no ice, but made from clay so a little water seeps through and evaporates and cools the rest.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shatit: you drink"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shatit: you drink</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishʔəvun (imperf): they draw water"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yishʔəvun (imperf): they draw water</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Dengar bagitu ju, Rut tondo sampe di tana. Ais dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta minta tarima kasi, bapa! Ma beta mau tanya bagini. Bapa pasti su tau, beta ni, bukan orang sini. Jadi, akurang ko bapa taro mata sang beta, deng kasi tunju hati bae sang beta?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, Rut bowed to the ground. Then she said, &lt;&lt;I give thanks, father/sir! But I'd like to ask this. Surely you already know that I am not a local person (from here). So (consequently), why is it that you are paying attention (lit: placing eyes) on me, and showing a good liver to me?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatippol (nfl): fall (bow down quickly)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vatippol (nfl): fall (bow down quickly)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-paneyha: on her face"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕal-paneyha: on her face</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatishtachu (chwh hitshtafal): bow down, as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vatishtachu (chwh hitshtafal): bow down, as a suppliant or before a superior. Hendiadys, response to a favor by a powerful person who could have harmed her (like Abigail in 1 Samuel). It's the only honor Boaz gets, while Ruth gets a lot out of it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maduaʕ: why?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">maduaʕ: why?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʔti chen: why have I found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">matsaʔti chen: why have I found favor (make good = flirt)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hakiyreni (nkr hif): to recognize me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hakiyreni (nkr hif): to recognize me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nakhriyyah (fem): foreigner"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">nakhriyyah (fem): foreigner</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ju Bo'as manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Batúl. Beta su tau. Ma samua orang di sini ada carita lu pung hati bae kasi lu pung mama mantu waktu lu pung laki su mati. Dong ju carita lu ada jalan kasi tenga lu pung mama-bapa deng lu pung kampong asal, ko datang di orang laen dong pung teng-tenga, biar sonde kanál sang dong.<bt>[So] Bo'as responded saying, &lt;&lt;It's true. I do already know. But everyone here has been telling about your good liver to your mother-in-law when your husband died. They also tell that you have left your parents and your village of origins, to come into the midst of other/different people, even though you do not know them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hugged huggad (ngd hof): is announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hugged huggad (ngd hof): is announced to me [thoroughly - inf abs]; I have been informed of the whole situation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmotekh: your mother-in-law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chəmotekh: your mother-in-law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vataʕazvi: you left"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vataʕazvi: you left</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moladtekh: your family"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">moladtekh: your family</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təmowl: yesterday"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">təmowl: yesterday</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shilshowm: three days ago - until"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shilshowm: three days ago - until recently</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Jadi beta minta ko TUHAN,<bt>So (consequently), I ask that the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">andia botong orang Isra'el pung Allah,<bt>that is we-exc people of Isra'el's God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">balas lu pung hati bae samua!<bt>repay/reward all of your good liver!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Beta minta ko Dia kasi berkat bam-banya sang lu,<bt>I ask that He give many blessings to you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal lu pung hati bae sang mama Omi.<bt>because of your good liver to mother Omi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar ko TUHAN yang jaga sang lu di sini,<bt>May the LORD watch/guard you here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal lu cari lindung di Dia,<bt>because you seek protection in Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sama ke ayam ana dong cari lindung di bawa ayam mai pung sayap.&gt;&gt;<bt>like young chickens seek protection under the wings of the hen.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Not clear in most languages."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cn) Not clear in most languages.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) This gets the protection part"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cr) This gets the protection part of it, but ignores the feathers.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəshallem (shlm piʕel jussive): may he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yəshallem (shlm piʕel jussive): may he reward, recompense</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paʕəlekh: your work"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">paʕəlekh: your work</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maskurtekh: your wages"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">maskurtekh: your wages</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəlemah: complete"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shəlemah: complete</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʔt: you came"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">baʔt: you came</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lachəSot (chSh inf): to find refuge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lachəSot (chSh inf): to find refuge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hachat-knafayw: under his wings - not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hachat-knafayw: under his wings - not a clear metaphor to Pidgin speakers</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais Rut balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa, é! Biar beta bukan bapa pung orang karjá, ma beta mau bekin sanáng bapa pung hati tarús. Te bapa su kasi kuat beta pung hati, ais kasi tunju hati bae sang beta ju.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Rut responded saying, &lt;&lt;Father/sir, é! Even though I am not your worker, nevertheless I want to please your liver continually. Cuz (elaboration) you have strengthened/encouraged my liver, and have also shown your good liver (goodness, kindness, generosity) to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔemtsaʔ-chen: may I continue to find"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔemtsaʔ-chen: may I continue to find favor, may you continue to accept me. Hubbard: this very formula apparently was a convention of polite speech that served to conclude (in some cases, dramatically) a conversation (Gen. 33:15; 2 Sam. 16:4; cf. Gen. 34:11; 1 Sam. 1:18). Ruth employed it in the same way here. Given the narratorʔs cleverness, however, one would not be overreaching to hear in her wish a veiled desire to see Boaz again.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔədoniy: my master. In Pidgin you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔədoniy: my master. In Pidgin you donʔt address anybody as ʔmy boss,ʔ but you do address them as ʔboss.ʔ</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nichamtani (nchm piʕel): you have consoled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">nichamtani (nchm piʕel): you have consoled me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dibarta ʕal-lev: you speak to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">dibarta ʕal-lev: you speak to the heart; you speak kindly</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔehyeh: I will [not] be. Hubbard:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔehyeh: I will [not] be. Hubbard: The imperfect verbal form of hyh is used here. F. W. Bush shows from usage elsewhere that the form should be taken as future (Ruth, 124-25).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shifchatekha: your maidservant"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shifchatekha: your maidservant</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Waktu dong barenti ko makan, ju Bo'as kasi tau sang Rut bilang, &lt;&lt;Mari sini sa! Makan sama-sama deng botong. Ame ini roti sadiki, ais kalo suka, na, colo pi dalam anggor asam ju.&gt;&gt; Ais ju Rut pi dudu deka deng orang karjá dong. Tarús Bo'as kasi dia jagong bakar ko makan. Rut makan sampe kinyang, deng masi ada sisa ju.<bt>When they stopped to eat, Bo'as told Rut saying, &lt;&lt;Come over here! Eat together with us-exc. Take some of this bread, and if you like, na, dip [it] into this sour wine.&gt;&gt; Then Rut went and sat near the workers. Then2 Bo'as gave her roasted corn/grain to eat. Rut ate until full, and there was some leftover too. [EXEG: NLT, CEV, TN, HCE]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goshi (ngsh imperv fem): approach! come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">goshi (ngsh imperv fem): approach! come here!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həlom: here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">həlom: here</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="min-hallechem: some of [our]. UBS: It"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">min-hallechem: some of [our]. UBS: It is important to indicate in an expression such as "have a piece of bread" that this is something which Boaz is giving to Ruth. He is not commanding her to eat her own food, but rather is offering her something.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tavalt: dip"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">Tavalt: dip</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pitekh: your bit (of pita bread)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">pitekh: your bit (of pita bread)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chomets: vinegar, sour wine (like Subway"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chomets: vinegar, sour wine (like Subway sandwiches)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teshev: sit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">teshev: sit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsad: from the side. Hubbard: Precisely"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tsad: from the side. Hubbard: Precisely where, however, did she sit? What attitude or status was implied? According to Campbell, the rather unusual phrase mittsad  ("at the flanks of"; cf. [with mountains] 1 Sam. 23:26; 2 Sam. 13:34) underscored Ruthʔs modesty (i.e., she sat beside, not among, the reapers).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsbaT: he held out for her,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yitsbaT: he held out for her, passed to her. UBS: Even in late Hebrew the verb is very rare and used only in contexts describing that part of a vessel or jar which one touches in handling it. Translators of ancient versions did not understand the meaning of this Hebrew verb, and they read into it another Hebrew verb meaning "to heap up." This reading is also found in some modern translations and is defended by some commentators who argue that the meaning of "to pass" would be incorrect in speaking of what Boaz did. However, the meaning of "to heap up" should not be employed... since there is no certainty with regard to the meaning of the term, the rendering of "to pass" seems to be the most satisfactory, at least until new evidence as to its meaning is found.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kali (kalah construct): parched grain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kali (kalah construct): parched grain</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisbaʕ: she became satiated, had enough"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tisbaʕ: she became satiated, had enough (this doesnʔt mean she pigged out, just ate all she wanted)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totar (ytr hif): had plenty left"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">totar (ytr hif): had plenty left over</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00966c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15-16" />Waktu dia kambali di kabón ko pili ame jagong rote sisa yang orang karjá dong sonde ika ame, ju Bo'as kasi tau dia pung orang karjá dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar bae-bae! Jang ganggu sang dia. Kasi biar ko dia pili ame jagong di mana sa. Deka deng itu ikatan dong ju, sonde apa-apa. Beta sonde mara kalo bosong tarek satu-dua puler dari jagong yang bosong su ikat dong, ais kasi tenga ko biar dia pili ame. Jang mara sang dia, deng jang bekin malu sang dia ju.&gt;&gt;<bt>When she returned to the field to retrieve barley/sorghum that the workers had not tied/bound/bundled, then Bo'as told his workers saying, &lt;&lt;Listen carefully! Don't bother her. Let her retreive the grain wherever. Near the bundles is OK too. I will not be angry if you-pl pull out one or two grainheads from the grain that you have already tied, and leave it there for her to retrieve. Don't get angry with her, and don't embarrass her either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləlaqqeT (piʕel inf): to pick up."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ləlaqqeT (piʕel inf): to pick up. UBS: A translation such as ”when she got up... “ can be misleading, for it might imply that at this very time Boaz ordered his servants to treat her with special consideration, thus suggesting that Ruth was still present when Boaz gave the order to his servants.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beyn (bayin): between. This is pushing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">beyn (bayin): between. This is pushing the custom a little; but Boaz is showing chesed.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəmariym: the sheaves (already tied up)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕəmariym: the sheaves (already tied up)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʔ takhlimuha (klm hif): do not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">loʔ takhlimuha (klm hif): do not shame her</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shol tashollu (shll hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shol tashollu (shll hif inf abs): make sure you pull out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsəvatiym: tied bundles of grain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tsəvatiym: tied bundles of grain</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəzavtem: leave them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕəzavtem: leave them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vloʔ tigʕəru-bah: donʔt rebuke her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vloʔ tigʕəru-bah: donʔt rebuke her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Rut karjá di kabón satu hari anteru. Waktu matahari mau tanggalám, ju dia puku kasi kaluar isi dari tangke dong. Dia pung isi, satu bakul ponu.<bt>Rut worked in the field for a full day. When the sun was about to set, she beat [it] to separate the grain from the stalks. The yield was one full basket. [EXEG: NLT, HCE]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatachbot: beat a plant or a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vatachbot: beat a plant or a tree to make its yield fall off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeyfah: unit of dry measure of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔeyfah: unit of dry measure of 22 liters or 0.6 bushels; equals 10 omer. About the size of a sack of rice in the supermarket.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="səʕoriym (pl): barley"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">səʕoriym (pl): barley</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, itu bakul tu, satu <span class="Italic">eyfah.</span> Satu <span class="Italic">eyfah</span> tu, muat kira-kira 22 liter.<bt>The Ibrani language writes saying, that basket was one <span class="Italic">eyfah.</span> One <span class="Italic">eyfah</span> holds about 22 liters.</bt></note><v n="18" />Ais dia bawa pulang itu bakul pi kampong Betlehem, ju kasi tunju dia pung hasil sang dia pung mama mantu. Ais dia ju kasi kaluar makanan sisa dari makan siang tadi, ko kasi dia pung mama mantu.<bt>Then she brought that basket home to the village of Betlehem, and showed her yield to her mother-in-law. Then she also took out the leftover food from lunch earlier, to give to her mother-in-law.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tisseʔ (nsʔ hif): she carried off,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tisseʔ (nsʔ hif): she carried off, took</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totseʔ (ytsʔ hif): she took out,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">totseʔ (ytsʔ hif): she took out, produced</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattereʔ: she saw? she showed? Textual"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vattereʔ: she saw? she showed? Textual difference.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hotirah (ytr hif): she had left"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hotirah (ytr hif): she had left over</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="savʕah: her fulness (left over)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">savʕah: her fulness (left over)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00968c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais Na'omi tanya sang Rut bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Tadi lu pili ini jagong dong di mana, é? Lu karjá di sapa pung kabón? Biar ko Tuhan Allah kasi berkat bam-banya sang orang yang taro kira sang lu tadi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Na'omi asked Rut saying, &lt;&lt;Awii [+amazment]! Earlier where did you retrieve grain from, é? You worked in whose field? May God give many blessings to the person who paid attention to you earlier.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Rut manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama! Itu tuan kabón di situ, dia pung nama Bo'as.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 Rut answered saying, &lt;&lt;Mother! The owner of that field is named Bo'as.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔanah: to where?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔanah: to where?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yhi: it will happen, may it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yhi: it will happen, may it happen</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makiyrekh (nkr hif partcpl): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">makiyrekh (nkr hif partcpl): the one who recognized you, took notice of you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taged (ngd hif): she announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">taged (ngd hif): she announced</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Na'omi kasi tau dia pung ana mantu bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar ko TUHAN Allah kasi berkat bam-banya sang Bo'as. Te Tuhan sonde lupa kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang kotong yang idop, deng kotong pung laki yang su mati dong ju. Beta kasi tau sang lu bagini: Bo'as tu, kotong pung keluarga dekat. Botong bilang, dia yang ada &lt;hak tabús&gt;. Dia pung arti bilang, dia ada pung hak ko kawin ame sang lu, ko kasi turunan sang lu pung laki yang su mati tu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Na'omi told her daughter-in-law saying, &lt;&lt;May the LORD God give many blessings to Bo'as. Cuz (elaboration) the Lord has not forgotten to show His good liver to we-inc who live, and also to our dead husbands. I'll tell you this: Bo'as is our-inc close relative. We-exc say he has &lt;the right to redeem&gt;. That means he has the right to marry you, to give descendants to your husband who has died.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: TN, Hubbard. Explication following TN and HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕazav: he has not let go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕazav: he has not let go</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaSdo: his obligation to the covenant,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chaSdo: his obligation to the covenant, to his people. Probably the subject of ʔasher loʔ ʕazav chaSdow. The spirit of obligation to the family has not left the living or the dead.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metiym (mwt partcpl pl): those who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">metiym (mwt partcpl pl): those who are dead</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="migoʔəlenu (gʔl ptcpl): redeemer, one of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">migoʔəlenu (gʔl ptcpl): redeemer, one of the class of people with the right to buy back something</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kapala Agama dong pung Atoran 25:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Rut kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama! Tadi Bo'as ju kasi tau sang beta bilang, &lt;Beso datang di sini lai. Lu bole iko deka deng beta pung orang karjá dong sampe musim koru abis samua.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Rut told her saying, &lt;&lt;Mother! Earlier Bo'as also told me saying, &lt;Tomorrow come here again. You may follow close to my workers until the harvest season is completely finished.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam: in addition"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">gam: in addition</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tidbaqiyn: you may stick with (probably"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tidbaqiyn: you may stick with (probably with the female workers; nəʕariym covers both sexes, but he has told them to stay away from her)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killu (klh piʕel): they complete, finish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">killu (klh piʕel): they complete, finish</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Na'omi balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu sa! Itu tanda bae. Te lu bisa karjá sama-sama deng dia pung parampuan karjá dong sampe musim koru abis. Kalo di orang laen pung kabón bisa sa ada yang ganggu sang lu. Ma di Bo'as pung kabón dong, lu aman sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Na'omi responded saying, &lt;&lt;OK! That's a good sign. Cuz (elaboration)) you can work together with his female workers until the end of the harvest season. If [you were] in a different person's field, it is possible that someone might bother you. But is Bo'as' fields, you are safe/secure!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: field or fields? vs. 23 plus ‘rich man’ implies pl.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kallatah: her daughter-in-law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kallatah: her daughter-in-law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bati: my daughter. Not used in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bati: my daughter. Not used in Pidgin; either the name or nothing fits here.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tetsʔiy: you will go out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tetsʔiy: you will go out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʔ yifgʕu-bakh: the men will not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">loʔ yifgʕu-bakh: the men will not fall upon you, meet you with hostility, harm you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Jadi siang hari Rut pili jagong rote sisa di Bo'as pung kabón dong badeka-badeka deng dia pung parampuan karjá dong sampe musim koru jagong rote deng gandum abis. Malam hari, na, dia tenga tarús deng dia pung mama mantu.<bt>So (consequently) during the day Rut retreived barley/sorghum in Bo'as' fields, near his female workers until the end of the barley/sorghum and wheat harvest season. At night, na, she kept living with her mother-in-law.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tidbaq: she stuck with them, hung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tidbaq: she stuck with them, hung out with</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kəlot (klh inf): complete, finish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kəlot (klh inf): complete, finish</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəʕón doriym: barley"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shəʕón doriym: barley</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chiTTiym: wheat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chiTTiym: wheat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rut deng Bo'as di tampa bekin barisi padi<bt>Rut and Bo'as in the place of cleaning grain</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Satu kali, Na'omi kasi tau dia pung ana mantu Rut bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Sakarang su dia pung waktu kalo beta cari laki yang bae kasi sang lu, ko biar lu ada pung ruma tangga sandiri, deng bisa idop aman tarús di situ. Ko karmana?<bt>One time, Na'omi told her daughter-in-law Rut saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. It's now time for me to look for a good husband for you, so that you have your own household/family, and can live safe/secure there. Or how? [= How about it? What do you think?] [EXEG: Hubbard, TN, NLT, CEV, HCE notes (manoaəch: resting-place, like mnuchah in 1. For animals, exiles, those without kin, soul, Covenant Box. A place where you can feel secure. This implies a husband of her own, not a good boarding house.)] [NOTE to daughter translations: drop the tag question at the end if it is awkward. It is just reflecting an RQ in the Hebrew, but unnessecary in some of our lgs.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chmotah: her mother-in-law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chmotah: her mother-in-law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haloʔ: isn't it so?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">haloʔ: isn't it so?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manoaəch: resting-place, like mnuchah in 1."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">manoaəch: resting-place, like mnuchah in 1. For animals, exiles, those without kin, soul, Covenant Box. A place where you can feel secure. This implies a husband of her own, not a good boarding house.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitav-lakh: it will be good for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yitav-lakh: it will be good for you (tov)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Dengar bae-bae. Lu masi inga itu laki-laki, nama Bo'as, to? Dia yang ator ko biar lu pili jagong rote di balakang dia pung parampuan orang karjá dong. Dia bakelu deng kotong dari beta pung laki yang su mati. Ini malam ju banya orang rame-rame mau bakumpul di tampa inja padi. Nanti Bo'as ada di situ ju.<bt>Listen carefully. You still remember that man named Bo'as, right? [+tag] He is the one who arranged so that you could retrieve barley/sorghum behind his female workers. He is family/related to my dead husband. Tonight many people will festively gather at the place of treading on rice/grain. Later Bo'as will be there too. [EXEG: TN, Hubbard. NLT, Festive occasion = Implicit to explicit. Heb winnow and thresh both used, but heavy here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕatah: now"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕatah: now</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haloʔ: isn't it true that ...?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">haloʔ: isn't it true that ...?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="modaʕtanu: our distant relative"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">modaʕtanu: our distant relative</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayiyt: you have become"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hayiyt: you have become</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕərotayw: one of his female workers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">naʕərotayw: one of his female workers</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneh: calls special attention to what"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hinneh: calls special attention to what she is about to say</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zoreh (partcpl masc sg): he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">zoreh (partcpl masc sg): he is winnowing (beating the barley to break the grain off the stalks, then tossing up pitchforks full of it so the wind can blow the part you canʔt eat away)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goren: threshing floor, the open space"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">goren: threshing floor, the open space where they winnow the barley. JR sounds like he is finishing off the winnowing and is celebrating, maybe with some local ceremony or par</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hasəʕorim: barley"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hasəʕorim: barley</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Jadi beta pung mau, bagini: lu pi mandi dolo. Ais taro minya wangi sadiki, deng pake pakean yang alus ju. Ais itu, lu turun pi itu tampa inja padi tu. Ma jaga bae-bae. Tunggu ko Bo'as su makan-minum abis dolo, baru kasi biar ko dia lia lu ada di situ.<bt>So (consequently), this is what I want [you to do]: go bathe first. Then put on a bit of aromatic oil, and wear nice/fine clothes too. Then go down to that place of treading on grain. But be careful. Wait so that Bo'as has already eaten, only then let him see that you are there. [EXEG: TN, NLT, Hubbard]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rachatst: wash yourself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">rachatst: wash yourself</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sakht (swk): anoint yourself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">sakht (swk): anoint yourself</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samt: put on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">samt: put on</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="simltkha (qereʔ simlotayikh): your dress"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">simltkha (qereʔ simlotayikh): your dress</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕalaykh: on yourself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕalaykh: on yourself</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yardti (1st person, qeri 2nd person):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yardti (1st person, qeri 2nd person): you go down</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tiwwadʕi (ydʕ nif): unbeknownst to him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔal-tiwwadʕi (ydʕ nif): unbeknownst to him, don't let him know you are there; don't make yourself known, become known</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalto leʔkhol vlishtot: finished eating and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kalto leʔkhol vlishtot: finished eating and drinking (Hebrews don't just say "eat"; they say "eat and drink")</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Makan abis, pasti dia mau tidor. Tagal su galáp, andia ko lu musti lia bae-bae dia pi tidor di mana. Kalo dia su tidor, na, lu iko pi situ ju. Buka salimut yang tutu ame dia pung kaki ko sein sang dia,<bt>After eating, surely he will want to sleep. Because it [will] already be dark, that is why you must watch carefully to see where he goes to sleep. When he is asleep, na, you go there too. Open/undo the blanket that is covering his feet/legs as a sign to him, then you also sleep/lay down there. Bo'as knows our customs/traditions/law, so (consequently) he will tell you what you must do.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: implicit, dark so everybody can't easily see who is where and what is going on. (See also TN, Hubbard). Ask for protection/marriage --see Hubbard, CEV note, HCE note. Elevation around 3,000 ft so probably blanket.]</bt><note reference="3:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang yang pintar so'al Alkitab dong bilang, ini jadi tanda 1) tagal Bo'as jadi kelu yang pung hak urus sang Rut, sakarang dia yang musti jaga sang Rut, deng 2) Rut siap kalo Bo'as mau kawin deng dia, iko dia pung hak.<bt>People who are knowledgable about the Bible (=experts) say this is a sign 1) because he is a family/relative who has the right/authority to make arrangements for Rut, now he must guard/watch over Rut, and 2) Rut is ready if Bo'as wants to marry her, according to his right.</bt></note>ais lu ju tidor di situ. Bo'as tau botong pung adat, jadi nanti dia yang kasi tau lu musti bekin karmana.&gt;&gt;<Annotation class="General" selectedText="bshakhvo: when he lies down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bshakhvo: when he lies down</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vgillit (glh piʕel imperv): you uncover"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vgillit (glh piʕel imperv): you uncover (doesn't say what is covering his feet: sheet, blanket, robe, ...). At 3,000 feet elevation, it would be a blanket [SS]. The action is understood as a request for Boaz's protection.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="margəlotayw: the place of his feet."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">margəlotayw: the place of his feet. Hubbard: Outside Ruth, it occurs only in Dan. 10:6, where it means "legs" (paired with "arms"), and Campbell (p. 121) accepts that meaning here. Nevertheless, three observations favor the consensus meaning "place of feet." First, the widely differing contexts of Dan.  10 and Ruth  3 leave open the possibility that the word has a different nuance in each. Second, that marGølOt derives from the word reg=el, "foot," suggests a meaning closer to "foot" than "legs." Third, according to GKC, § § 124a-b, the -Ot  ending identifies the word as a "plural of local extension" which refers to a place or area. Indeed, later in the chapter, the word definitely has a local sense (vv. 7, 8, 14). In sum, the word probably meant "place of feet," and corresponded to məraʔochot, "place of head" (Gen. 28:11, 18; 1 Sam. 19:13, 16; 1 K. 19:6); so Joüon, p. 69; Sasson, pp. 69-70; et al.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shakhavti (1st person, qeriʔ 2nd person):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shakhavti (1st person, qeriʔ 2nd person): you lie down. JR she doesn't tell Ruth what to say.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yagid: (ngd hif): he will announce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yagid: (ngd hif): he will announce to you, explain to you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʕəsiyn (paragogic n): what you are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">taʕəsiyn (paragogic n): what you are to do</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00960c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju Rut manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu. Nanti beta bekin iko bagitu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Rut responded saying, &lt;&lt;Fine [+word of acquiescence]. I will do that.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="6" />Ais dia turun pi tampa inja padi. Ju dia bekin iko dia pung mama mantu pung pasán samua.<bt>So she went down to the place of treading on grain. And she did according to everything her mother-in-law had instructed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwatah (tswh piʕel): ordered her to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tsiwwatah (tswh piʕel): ordered her to do</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Waktu Bo'as makan-minum abis, ju dia rasa kinyang. Ais dia pi tidor di tampa tumpuk padi pung sablá. Tunggu sampe dia su sono, ju Rut pi diam-diam di Bo'as pung tampa. Ais dia buka salimut yang ada di Bo'as pung kaki, ju tidor di situ.<bt>When Bo'as had finished eating, he felt full/satiated. So he went to lay down/sleep on the other/far side of a pile of grain. Waiting until he was sound asleep, then Rut quietly went to Bo'as place. Then she opened/undid the blanket that was at Bo'as feet/legs, and laid down/slept there. [EXEG: NLT, TN, Hubbard; padi here generic for ‘grain’ as in Heb. NOTE to daughter translations: careful about open the blanket at Bo'as feet, cuz that is ambiguous--it could be the blanket she brought. The intent here is his blanket at his feet.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyoʔkhal ... vayyesht: he ate and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vayyoʔkhal ... vayyesht: he ate and drank = he had his supper</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyTav: [his heart] felt good"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yiyTav: [his heart] felt good</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biqtseh: at the end, the border,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">biqtseh: at the end, the border, edge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəremah: the pile"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕəremah: the pile</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laT: secrecy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">laT: secrecy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tgal (glh piʕel): she uncovered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tgal (glh piʕel): she uncovered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marglotayw: the place at his feet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">marglotayw: the place at his feet</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishkov: she lay down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tishkov: she lay down</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Kira-kira su tenga malam, ju Bo'as takuju bangun. Ais dia balik badan, ju dia takuju, te ada satu parampuan yang tidor di dia pung kaki!<bt>Around the middle of the night, Bo'as suddenly awoke. He turned his body and was startled, cuz (elaboration) there was a woman sleeping at his feet!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətsi: middle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chətsi: middle</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yechərad: he was startled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yechərad: he was startled</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yillafet (lpt nif): he turned towards"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yillafet (lpt nif): he turned towards</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shokhevet (partcpl fem): lying there"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shokhevet (partcpl fem): lying there</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marglotayw: in the place at his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">marglotayw: in the place at his feet</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ais Bo'as tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ko lu ni, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Bo'as asked her saying, &lt;&lt;Who are you? [+demand]&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00970c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Rut manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, Rut, yang ke bapa pung parampuan karjá dong. Ma bapa ju yang &lt;hak tabús&gt; sang beta. Dia pung arti bilang, bapa ada pung hak ko kawin ame sang beta, ko kasi turunan sang beta pung laki yang su mati tu. Jadi beta minta ko bapa tutu ame sang beta pake ujung salimut ni, ko jadi tanda bilang, bapa mau kawin ame sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Rut replied saying, &lt;&lt;I am Rut, who is like one of your/father's worker women. But you are also the one who has the &lt;right to redeem&gt; me. That means you are the one with the right to marry me, to give descendants to my dead husband. So (consequently) I ask that you cover me with the end/corner of this blanket, as a sign that you will marry me.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: TN, HCE, Hubbard]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="farasta: spread out the edge of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">farasta: spread out the edge of your cloak. One way to claim someone as wife, like giving a girl a ring today. See Ezekiel 16:8.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khnafekha: the corner, edge, skirt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">khnafekha: the corner, edge, skirt</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goʔel (gʔl ptcpl): one who can"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">goʔel (gʔl ptcpl): one who can do the duty of the male relative of someone who has died leaving a childless widow, to deliver her from childlessness by marrying her; the deliverer or redeemer. Also carries the meaning of one who can make a claim in property law, to buy back something that has been sold, or buy someone out of slavery, for the family, which is how Boaz justifies marrying a foreigner to the community. Hubbard: Sasson observes that, except for the legal precision required by the proceedings of ch. 4 (vv. 5, 10), the book no longer mentions her Moabite origin; cf. "Ruth" (4:13).</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 16:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais Bo'as heran, ju omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Beta minta ko TUHAN kasi berkat sang lu! Bisa sa, lu cari laki dari ana muda dong di sini yang kaya, ko sonde. Ma lu sonde bekin bagitu. Lu ni, talalu bae! Te lu kasi tunju sayang deng hormat tarús sang lu pung laki yang su mati pung kelu dong. Lu pung hati bae sakarang ni, lebe hebat dari yang lu su kasi tunju sang mama Omi dolu tu.<bt>Then Bo'as was amazed, and spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Awii! [+amazed] I ask that the LORD give blessing to you! Just can [=it could have been] that you looked for one of the young men here, whether rich or not. But you didn't do that. You are so/too good! Cuz (elaboration) you continue to show love and respect for the family of your dead husband. Your good liver (goodness, kindness, grace, generosity) now is even more impressive than what you have shown for mother Omi previously. [EXEG: TN, HCE, Hubbard] [NOTE to daughter translations: ‘Daughter’ and ‘younger sibling’ are both inappropriate address in these RL lgs for possible marriage partner. Mama Omi, rather than Tanta or Susi.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="brukhah (partcpl pass fem): blessed, to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">brukhah (partcpl pass fem): blessed, to be praised, favored by Yahweh</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biti: my daughter (in Pidgin, in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">biti: my daughter (in Pidgin, in this situation, would it be "sista"? - JO in this context, better just "Rut")</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heyTavt (yTb hif): you have done"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">heyTavt (yTb hif): you have done a good thing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaSdekh (cheSed): your loyalty to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chaSdekh (cheSed): your loyalty to the family</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʔachəron: future, coming after, your latest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">haʔachəron: future, coming after, your latest act of loyalty (what she is doing right now) is greater than the first one</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riʔshon: the first [act] of loyalty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">riʔshon: the first [act] of loyalty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lbilti lekhet: without going after the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lbilti lekhet: without going after the young guys</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bachuriym: fully grown young man, not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bachuriym: fully grown young man, not yet married - the eligible bachelors</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dal: low, helpless"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">dal: low, helpless</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕashiyr: rich"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕashiyr: rich</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi jang taku! Te beta mau bekin iko lu pung mau samua. Jang jadi pikiran, te samua orang bésar di ini kota dong su tau bilang, lu ni parampuan yang hati bae deng rajin.<bt>So (consequently), don't be afraid! Cuz (elaboration) I'm going to do everything that you want. Don't worry, cuz (elaboration) all the important people in this city already know that you are a good-livered and hard-working/diligent woman. [EXEG: HCE notes, (kol-shaʕar: the whole gate, all the people who run the affairs of the city), TN, Hubbard notes]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biti: my daughter - &quot;sista&quot;? -"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">biti: my daughter - "sista"? - JO in this context, better omitted</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tiyrʔi: donʔt be frightened"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔal-tiyrʔi: donʔt be frightened</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔmriy: what you said"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">toʔmriy: what you said</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeʕəseh llakh: why the dagesh?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔeʕəseh llakh: why the dagesh?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yodeaʕ (partcpl masc): knowing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yodeaʕ (partcpl masc): knowing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kol-shaʕar: the whole gate, all the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kol-shaʕar: the whole gate, all the people who run the affairs of the city</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕammiy: my people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕammiy: my people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeshet chayil ʔat: you are a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔeshet chayil ʔat: you are a woman who is qualified, worthy, brave, strong. Smart Guys 31:10 good kine wahine dat stay strong inside</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ma sakarang masi ada satu hal lai. Sonde sala bilang, beta ni lu pung laki yang su mati pung kelu yang &lt;hak tabús&gt; sang lu. Ma ada satu orang laen yang lebe deka dari beta. Jadi dia yang ada hak putus ko mau kawin ame sang lu. Kalo dia sonde mau, baru beta ada hak.<bt>But now there is still one more thing [that must be attended to]. It is not wrong to say that I am your husband's family/relative who has the &lt;right to redeem&gt; you. But there is another person who is closer than me. So (consequently) he has the right to decide to marry you (first). If he doesn't want to, only then do I have the right. [NOTE to daughter translations: check if deka or kaka works better in your lg.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamnam: indeed."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔamnam: indeed.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ki ʔim goʔel: because if I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ki ʔim goʔel: because if I am the one responsible for marrying you. ʔm the Rabbis left unvocalized because they had the consonants but weren't sure of the vowels. It's true that I am a goʔel, but the other guy has legal precedence. A lot of new information is stuck in along with the main events. Naomi may not realize that the other goʔel has precedence; but she might. He is unnamed, which is unusual in the Old Testament.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rut 2:20</note><v n="13" />Jadi beta usul bagini: ini malam tenga di sini sa. Beso beta pi ba'omong deng dia. Kalo dia sadia ko urus deng kawin sang lu, na, biar bagitu sa. Ma kalo sonde, na, beta sumpa pake Tuhan yang Idop pung nama bilang, beta sandiri yang nanti urus deng kawin ame sang lu. Botong pung adat di sini bilang, beta yang mau &lt;tabús ame&gt; sang lu. Naa, tidor di situ sampe siang su.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) I suggest like this: just stay here tonight. Tomorrow I will go talk with him. If he is prepared to be responsible for and marry you, na, just let it be like that. But if not, na, I swear using the name of the Living God, that I myself with be responsible for and marry you. Our customs/traditions here say that I am the one who will &lt;redeem&gt; you. Naa, [+shift] go ahead and sleep there until daylight.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: NLT, Hubbard, TN]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lini (lyn imperv): stay overnight. Boaz"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lini (lyn imperv): stay overnight. Boaz speaks in imperatives.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yigʔalekh: if he will take up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yigʔalekh: if he will take up the family's right in you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-loʔ yachpots (qal): if he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔim-loʔ yachpots (qal): if he is not willing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais Rut tidor di Bo'as pung kaki. Ma amper siang, waktu masi talalu galáp ko orang bisa kanál satu deng satu, ju Rut su bangun ko mau jalan. Te Bo'as su kasi tau memang bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde bae kalo orang dapa tau ada parampuan yang datang malam-malam di ini tampa inja padi.<bt>Then Rut slept at Bo'as feet. But before dawn, when it was still dark so that people could not recognise each other, then Rut got up to leave. Cuz (elaboration) Bo'as had told her beforehand saying, &lt;&lt;It's not good if people come to find out there was a woman who came at night to this place of treading on grain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marglotaw: the place at his feet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">marglotaw: the place at his feet</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bterom (qereʔ bterem): before"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bterom (qereʔ bterem): before</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yakir (nkr hif imperf): before anybody"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yakir (nkr hif imperf): before anybody can recognize his friend; before anybody can recognize her</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔet-reʕihu: before anybody can recognize his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔet-reʕihu: before anybody can recognize his counterpart</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwadaʕ (ydʕ nif): be known"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yiwwadaʕ (ydʕ nif): be known</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Mari, taro itu kain panas yang lu pake ko biar beta isi deng jagong rote.&gt;&gt; Ais dia ra'u jagong rote anam kali ko isi di Rut pung kain. Tarús dia bantu kasi pikol di Rut. Ais Bo'as pulang pi kampong ju.<bt>Come on, place that warm cloth that you are wearing so that I can fill it with sorghum/barley. Then he scooped up sorghum/barley six times to fill Rut's cloth. Then he helped load it on Rut (shoulder/back, for carrying heavy/bulky things). Then Bo'as also went back to the village. [EXEG (Hebrew text): majority ‘he’, minority ‘she’. TB, NRSV, NLT, HCE, TN take Boas. here. TEV, CEV, NASB, NET, Syriac, Vulgate take Ruth here, assuming the masculine is a mistake. Unit of measure not known. TN suggestion of 30kg is a bit suspect from a number of angles. Last sentence with ‘too’ follows HCE compromise of text plus context.] [CHECK: can you ‘pikol’ without a lalebat?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) How did she carry 60"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cn) How did she carry 60 lbs of barley in a cloak?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) 60 pounds isn't unimagineable from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z">(cr) 60 pounds isn't unimagineable from what I've seen in Mexico, but no need to push the imagination. As for the shawl, Na`omi had Ruth dress up, so it wouldn't have been the one she wore to work, but a dress up shawl, and 60 pounds might have split it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="havi (imperv): come on!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">havi (imperv): come on!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miTpachat: womanʔs cloak, wrapper, mantle, shawl."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">miTpachat: womanʔs cloak, wrapper, mantle, shawl. There are big ones and small ones.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔachəzi: grab hold of it, hold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔachəzi: grab hold of it, hold it out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamad (mdd qal): measured"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yamad (mdd qal): measured</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shesh-sʕorim: six [measures] of barley"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shesh-sʕorim: six [measures] of barley</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashet (shyt qal): put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yashet (shyt qal): put</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyavoʔ: he went. Syriac &amp; Vulg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vayyavoʔ: he went. Syriac &amp; Vulg "she went"; but that's in the next verse.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani sonde bilang itu ukuran pung bésar. Ma cukup barát sampe Bo'as musti tolong kasi pikol di Rut. Tulisan bahasa Ibrani banya tulis bilang, “dia (laki-laki, andia Bo'as)” yang pulang pi kampong. Ma ada saparu ju yang tulis bilang, “dia (parampuan, andia Rut)” yang pulang pi kampong.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible does not say how big the measure was. But it was heavy enough that Bo'as had to help load it on Rut. Most Ibrani language writings write saying, “3s (male, that is, Bo'as)” who went back to the village. But there are a few that write saying, “3s (female, that is Rut)” who went back to the village.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Waktu Rut sampe di ruma, ju dia pung mama mantu tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana tadi malam, ó?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Rut arrived home, her mother-in-law asked her saying, &lt;&lt;How [did it go] last night, ó?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mi-ʔat: how did things go? But"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">mi-ʔat: how did things go? But not answered casually; it's a real inquiry.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vataged-lah (ngd hif narr): she announced,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vataged-lah (ngd hif narr): she announced, told, laid it out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Rut kasi tau samua-samua yang Bo'as bekin kasi sang dia,<bt>Then Rut told everything that Bo'as had done for her,</bt><v n="17" />ais tamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Dia ju ra'u kasi beta ini jagong rote. Ju dia bilang, &lt;Lu jang pulang pi mama mantu deng tangan kosong sa.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>and added saying, &lt;&lt;He also scooped up/out for me this sorghum/barley. And he said, &lt;You should not go home to your mother-in-law with empty hands.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔelay: only the vowel points and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔelay: only the vowel points and accent to show that they think a word should be there but the consonants are not in the text.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reyqam: empty, empty-handed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">reyqam: empty, empty-handed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ju Na'omi manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu sa! Sakarang lu musti sabar sa, ko tunggu kabar. Te su jalás bilang, Bo'as mau urus ini parkara deng sonde mau tunggu-tunggu lai. Pasti dia mau urus ini hari ju.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Na'omi responded saying, &lt;&lt;That's fine! Now you must just be patient to wait for news. Cuz (elaboration) it is clear that Bo'as is going to handle this issue and doesn't want to wait/delay any longer. Surely he will deal with it today.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəviy (yshb imperv): stay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shəviy (yshb imperv): stay</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tedʕiyn (ydʕ imperf): you find out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tedʕiyn (ydʕ imperf): you find out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yipol (npl imperf): what is going"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yipol (npl imperf): what is going to fall out, happen ( like throwing dice)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʔ yishqoT: he won't be at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">loʔ yishqoT: he won't be at peace</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killah (klh piʕel): it ends up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">killah (klh piʕel): it ends up, it turns out; he will bring it to a conclusion today. Chesed in action.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bo'as dudu parkara<bt>Bo'as sits an issue/case/dispute/ litigation [implies involving a recognised system and authority]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ais ju Bo'as pi di pintu maso kota ko mau dudu di situ. Di itu tampa, itu kota pung tua-tua biasa bakumpul ko barunding. Sampe deng sampe ju, dia pung kelu yang satu lai yang ada pung &lt;hak tabús&gt; ko bisa kawin ame sang Rut ju jalan lewat di situ. Ais Bo'as pange ame sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;We, bu! Mari dudu sini dolo! Te beta ada parlú.&gt;&gt; Ju itu orang datang dudu di situ.<bt>Then Bo'as went to the door/gate entering the city to sit there. In that place, the elders of that city often/normally gather to confer (w/each other). Upon arriving, his other relative who had the &lt;right to redeem&gt; to be able to marry Rut also walked by there. So Bo'as called out to him saying, &lt;&lt;We, older brother [+respect]! Come sit down over here! Cuz (elaboration) I have a need (= I need something from you).&gt;&gt; Then that person came and sat there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʕar: the city gate, where all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shaʕar: the city gate, where all the town affairs were transacted</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕover (partcpl masc): passing by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕover (partcpl masc): passing by</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dibber (piʕel): he spoke; whom he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">dibber (piʕel): he spoke; whom he had mentioned</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Surah (Swr imperv): turn aside!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">Surah (Swr imperv): turn aside!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvah-poh (yshv imperv): sit down here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shvah-poh (yshv imperv): sit down here</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəloni ʔalmoni: a certain person, used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">pəloni ʔalmoni: a certain person, used when a specific person is mentioned but not identified</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Tarús Bo'as pange ame sapulu tua-tua ko dudu jadi saksi bilang, &lt;&lt;Mari, bapa-bapa dong dudu sini ko dengar ini parkara.&gt;&gt; Ju dong dudu.<bt>Then Bo'as summoned ten elders to sit as witnesses saying, &lt;&lt;Come, (you) fathers sit here to hear this matter.&gt;&gt; So they sat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ziqney: elders, older men of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ziqney: elders, older men of the town</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Tarús Bo'as carita kasi dia pung kelu yang ada pung &lt;hak tabús&gt; di Rut bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Bu masi inga itu tana sapotong yang jadi kotong pung kelu Elimelek pung tana milik, ko? Dolu, waktu musim lapar, dia pi tana Moab, ais mati di sana. Sakarang dia pung janda, mama Na'omi, su pulang dari sana, ju mau jual itu tana.<bt>Then Bo'as told his relative who had the &lt;right to redeem&gt; Rut saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. You still remember that piece of land that our-inc relative Elimelek owned, right? Previously when there was famine, he went to Moab and then died there. Now his widow, mother Na'omi, has returned from there, and wants to sell that land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chelqat: allotment, portion. TWOT: The verb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chelqat: allotment, portion. TWOT: The verb is commonly used of parcelling out shares (RSV "allotments") of land (Num 26:53), whether by lot (Num 26:53), inheritance (Prov 17:2), or other forms of division (Prov 29:24)... The major share or tenure of land in the OT derived from tribal allotments (see h[e4leq), so that this feminine noun h[elqa= most commonly denotes the "share" or division of land made to the various tribes of Israel after the Conquest... Boaz appears to have farmed only part of Elimelechʔs land (Ruth 2:3; 4:3). By the time of the monarchy the term had become the general one for "field" (II Kgs 3:19), but often with the implication of inheritance (II Kgs 9:21). JR: the field was divided into individually owned plots. Naʕomi has the right to sell the land, but not just to anybody.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʔachinu: belonging to our brother Elimelek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lʔachinu: belonging to our brother Elimelek</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="machərah: will sell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">machərah: will sell</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shavah (shwb partcpl fem): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shavah (shwb partcpl fem): the one who returned</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dengar bagitu, ju beta pikir bagini: biar beta kasi tau bu dolo, tagal bu yang ada pung hak ko &lt;tabús ame&gt; itu tana. Te bu deng Elimelek satu turunan, na! Jadi, kalo bu mau béli ame itu tana, na, kasi tau memang, ko biar ini tua-tua dong jadi saksi. Ma kalo sonde, na, kasi tau di ini saksi dong pung muka ju, te beta mau béli. Yang batúl, bu yang ada pung hak lebe dolo. Ma kalo sonde mau, na, itu hak jato di beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>When I heard that, I thought like this: I should tell older brother first, because you are the one with the right to &lt;redeem (accomplishment)&gt; that land. Cuz (elaboration) you and Elimelek are in the same descent line! So (consequently) if you want to buy off that land, na, say so now, so that these elders can be witnesses. But if not, na, say so in front of these witnesses too, cuz (elaboration) I want to buy [it]. In actual fact, you have the right before me. But if you don't want to, na, that right falls to me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju itu orang manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu. Beta béli.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that person responded saying, &lt;&lt;Fine. I'll buy it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔegleh ʔaznkha (glh ʔozen): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔegleh ʔaznkha (glh ʔozen): I will uncover your ear, bring to your attention</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qneh (imperv): buy it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">qneh (imperv): buy it</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neged hayoshvim: in the presence of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">neged hayoshvim: in the presence of those sitting here</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕammiy: my people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕammiy: my people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagidah li (ngd hif imperv): announce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hagidah li (ngd hif imperv): announce it to me, say so publicly</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔdʕ (ydʔ): so I will know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔdʕ (ydʔ): so I will know</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔen zulatkha (zulah): there is not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔen zulatkha (zulah): there is not your removal, cessation. JR: Fulano has to step out of the succession legally.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔachəreykha: I am in line after"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔachəreykha: I am in line after you in case you donʔt do it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00971c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Tarús Bo'as kasi tau tamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Jang mara, ma bu musti inga, te kalo bu béli ame itu tana sapotong dari mama Omi, na, bu ju musti ame itu parampuan orang Moab, nama Rut. Te dia yang su kawin deng Elimelek pung ana yang su mati. Jadi bu musti kawin ame sang dia, ko kasi turunan sang dia pung laki yang su mati tu. Deng bagitu, dia pung tana pusaka sonde kaluar dari kotong pung kelu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Straightaway Bo'as added saying, &lt;&lt;Don't be angry [=I'm sorry.], but you need to remember, cuz (elaboration) if you buy off that piece ov land from mother Omi, na, you must also take that Moabite woman named Rut. Cuz (elaboration) she is the one who married Elimelek's child who has died. So (consequently) you must marry her to give descendants to her dead husband. In that way, his inheritance land will not go out from our-inc family.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qnyty (ktiv): I will buy, possibly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">qnyty (ktiv): I will buy, possibly "you buy the field and I will buy Ruth" though that doesnʔt fit the logic of the story; (qereʔ you will buy, the understanding of the rabbis)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhaqim (qwm hif inf): to raise"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ləhaqim (qwm hif inf): to raise up (a progeny); establish the name of the dead man. "Name" fits Okinawan traditions but might not fit Hawaiian traditions [SS]; check if "line" works for Hawaiian, because that might be best [OK SK].</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-nachlato: toward his inheritance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕal-nachlato: toward his inheritance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Itu orang manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, na, jang mara, ma beta sonde jadi béli. Te kalo beta béli, na, itu sama ke beta pung pusaka sandiri ilang buang. Beta pung pusaka deng beta pung ana akan jadi bu Elimelek pung turunan pung milik. Jadi, biar beta sonde usa béli. Biar adi Bo'as sa yang tabús ame itu tana deng kawin ame sang itu parampuan.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person responded saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, na, don't be angry, but it's not going to work out for me to buy [it]. Cuz (elaboration) if I buy it, na, that is as if my own inheritance completely disappears. My inheritance and my children would become the property of Elimelek's descendants. Just let younger sibling Bo'as be the one to redeem that land and marry that woman.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen: lest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">pen: lest</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔashchit (shchh hif): imperil, mess up;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔashchit (shchh hif): imperil, mess up; cloud an inheritance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nachəlatiy: my inheritance plans. &quot;Money&quot; isnʔt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">nachəlatiy: my inheritance plans. "Money" isnʔt the issue here, since it wasnʔt invented until centuries later. The estate is the issue; Elimilechʔs son outranks the other manʔs son for the main part of the inheritance. CHECK.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gəʔ ullatiy: my right of redemption"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">gəʔ ullatiy: my right of redemption</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />(Naa, dolu-dolu, waktu orang Isra'el mau sarakan dong pung hak ko tabús ame satu barang pi orang laen, dong buka dong pung sandal ko kasi itu orang. Itu jadi tanda sah di orang pung muka bilang, dong su sarakan itu hak.)<bt>(Naa, [+shift] long ago, when the people of Isra'el wanted to surrender their right to redeem something to someone else, they opened/took off their sandal to give to that person. That becomes a sign validating it in front of people that they have surrendered that right.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləfanim: formerly (the face)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ləfanim: formerly (the face)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-hagəʔulah: regarding the right to redeem"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕal-hagəʔulah: regarding the right to redeem</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-hatəmurah: regarding exchange, transfer of property"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕal-hatəmurah: regarding exchange, transfer of property</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləqayim (qwm piʕel): establish, confirm"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ləqayim (qwm piʕel): establish, confirm</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalaf: he pulls off, takes off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shalaf: he pulls off, takes off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕlo: his sandal, shoe. By Solomonʔs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">naʕlo: his sandal, shoe. By Solomonʔs time, when this may have been written, the deed would have been in written form, so here it heeds to be explained.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lreʕahu (raʕ): to the person he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">lreʕahu (raʕ): to the person he is dealing with, his companion, friend</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tʕudah: confirmation, attestation. JR: The levirate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tʕudah: confirmation, attestation. JR: The levirate is a species of law that actually covers a lot of cases.</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:7-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Carita Ulang so'al Jalan Idop 25:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Jadi waktu itu orang su sarakan dia pung hak tabús pi Bo'as bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar lu sa yang béli,&gt;&gt; ju dia buka dia pung sandal ko kasi pi Bo'as di tua-tua dong pung muka.<bt>So (consequently) when that person surrendered/handed over his right to redeem to Bo'as saying, &lt;&lt;Let it be you that buys [it],&gt;&gt; [NOTE: lexical ties resonating with vs.6] then he undid his sandal to give to Bo'as in front of the elders.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais Bo'as kasi tau tua-tua dong deng samua orang yang ada di situ bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa dong samua su jadi saksi ini hari. Itu hak su jato di beta. Beta kasi tau memang bilang, beta mau tabús ame dari mama Na'omi samua-samua yang dolu jadi milik dari bu Elimelek deng dia pung ana laki-laki, andia Kilyon deng Mahlon yang su mati dong.<bt>Then Bo'as told the elders and all the people present there saying, &lt;&lt;All you fathers/sirs are witnesses today. That right has fallen to me. I'm telling you right now that I am going to completely redeem everything from mother Na'omi that formerly was the property of Elimelek and his sons, that is Kilyon and Mahlon who have died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕedim: witnesses (predicative)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕedim: witnesses (predicative)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qaniytiy: I have acquired (title to)."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">qaniytiy: I have acquired (title to). This is what the goʔel would have gotten.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miyyad: from the hand of ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">miyyad: from the hand of = what is under her control</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Beta pung maksud bukan itu tana sandiri sa, te beta ju ame itu parampuan orang Moab, nama Rut, yang jadi Mahlon pung janda. Beta mau kawin ame sang dia, te beta su tabús itu hak. Deng bagitu, botong dua pung ana bisa jadi Mahlon pung turunan. Ju dia pung kelu deng dia pung orang kampong sonde akan lupa dia pung nama. Bosong ni yang jadi saksi ini hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>My intention is not just the land, cuz (elaboration) I will also take that Moabite woman, named Rut, who is Mahlon's widow. I'm going to marry her, cuz (elaboration) I have redeemed that right. In that way, the children from the two of us-exc can be/become Mahlon's descendants. And his family and the people from his village will not forget his name. You here are witnesses today.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhaqiym (qwm hif inf): in order"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ləhaqiym (qwm hif inf): in order to raise up, perpetuate</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nachəlato: over his inheritance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">nachəlato: over his inheritance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəloʔ-yikkaret (krt nif): so that it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vəloʔ-yikkaret (krt nif): so that it will not be cut off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔechayw: his brothers, relatives"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔechayw: his brothers, relatives</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʕar: from the gate = the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shaʕar: from the gate = the leaders of his town; keep a representation from Mahlonʔs line among the leaders of the town to keep the community strong.</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Carita Ulang so'al Jalan Idop 25:5-6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais ju tua-tua di itu kota deng samua orang yang ada bakumpul di situ manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Batúl, ó! Botong yang lia deng mata kapala sandiri. Botong ni yang jadi saksi.<bt>And so the elders of that city and all the people gathered there responded saying, &lt;&lt;That's true, ó! We-exc are the ones who have seen [it] with our own eyes. We-exc here are the ones who are the witnesses.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Itu parampuan yang maso dalam lu pung ruma,<bt>That woman who enters into your house,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">biar ko TUHAN bekin dia jadi ke Rahel deng Lea.<bt>May the LORD make her become like Rahel and Lea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te samua orang Isra'el turun dari dong dua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) all the people of Isra'el have descended from the two of them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar ko Tuhan bekin lu jadi orang bésar di fam Efrata,<bt>May the Lord make you become a big/important person in the Efrata clan, [EXEG: see discussion at 1:1-2 of Ephratha, and CEV rendering. On “Ephrathites” as a clan name, see Hubbard and TH.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng jadi orang yang pung nama bae di kota Betlehem.<bt>and become a person who has a good name/reputation in the city of Betlehem. [NOTE to daughter translations: these two stanzas are saying the same thing in good Hebrew poetic form.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="banu: they [the two free women"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">banu: they [the two free women who were Jacobʔs wives, but also their slaves who were his concubines] built the house of Israel. This brings in another case of putative descent; some of the tribes descended from the slaves, but were considered children of the slave owners.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shtehem (shnayim fem): the two of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shtehem (shnayim fem): the two of them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəseh (imperv masc): do, act"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʕəseh (imperv masc): do, act</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chayil: a power, a prominent person,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">chayil: a power, a prominent person, somebody with clout. May also mean "Make sure you produce a baby!"</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Carita Mula-mula 29:31</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Biar ko Tuhan kasi ana sang lu deng itu parampuan muda,<bt>May the Lord give you children with this young woman,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko biar bosong dua pung turunan jadi hebat,<bt>so the the two of you's descendants are/become great, [EXEG: Hubbard, CEV for point of comparison.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sama ke lu pung moyang Peres pung turunan,<bt>like your ancestor Peres' descendants,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang jadi Tamar deng Yahuda pung ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>who was Tamar and Yahuda's child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tamar (Genesis 38) had also married"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">Tamar (Genesis 38) had also married Judah as part of a deal to keep her dead husbandʔs name alive through her children. That line eventually included Jesus. CHECK.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitten: [Yahweh] will give"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yitten: [Yahweh] will give</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕərah: young woman"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">naʕərah: young woman</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tamar ju jadi orang asing di Isra'el. Dia kawin deng Yahuda ko mau kasi turunan sang dia pung laki yang su mati ju. Lia di <span class="Italic">Carita Mula-mula</span> 38.<bt>Tamar also was a foreigner in Isra'el. She also married/mated with Yahuda to give descendants to her dead husband. See in Genesis 38.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bo'as deng Rut dapa turunan<bt>Bo'as and Rut get offspring/descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais ju Bo'as kawin ame sang Rut. Waktu dong dua tidor bakumpul, TUHAN buka Rut pung tampa ana, ko biar dia bisa dudu parú. Ju dia barana ame satu ana laki-laki.<bt>After that, Bo'as married Rut. When the two of them slept together, the LORD opened Rut's womb [lit: child place], so that she could be pregnant. And she gave birth to a son.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The other place where Yahweh does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">The other place where Yahweh does something is when he breaks the famine in Judah.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="herayon: conception"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">herayon: conception</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00973c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Barana ame abis, ju parampuan di Betlehem dong kasi tau sang Na'omi bilang,<bt>After giving birth, the women of Betlehem told Na'omi saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Puji TUHAN!<bt>&lt;&lt;Praise the LORD!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Dia yang su kasi turunan sang lu,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who has given you offspring/descendants,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko biar lu pung kelu pung nama jang ilang buang.<bt>so that your family's name will not disappear.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar ko itu ana nanti jadi orang bésar di Isra'el.<bt>May that child later become a big/important person in Isra'el.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barukh: blessed, we should praise the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">barukh: blessed, we should praise the Lord</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʔ hishbit lakh goʔel hayom (shbt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">loʔ hishbit lakh goʔel hayom (shbt hif): he has not caused to cease for you (caused there not to be) one who exercises the right to keep your familyʔs name alive. CHECK.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishbiyt (shbt hif): he has [not]"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">hishbiyt (shbt hif): he has [not] caused to cease</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqareʔ shmo: and his name will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">yiqareʔ shmo: and his name will be called/mentioned. Probably refers to the baby. JR: "You lucky dog, you!" Everything get reinterpreted because things have changed so drastically.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Biar ko ini ana<bt>May this child</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bekin lu rasa ke su jadi muda kambali!<bt>make you feel you have become young again!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar ko ini ana<bt>May this child</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nanti jaga sang lu waktu su tua!<bt>guard/watch/take care of you when you are old!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te lu pung ana mantu yang barana ame sang ini ana cucu ni,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) you daughter-in-law who has given birth to this grandchild here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">su kasi tunju dia pung sayang sang lu.<bt>has shown her love for you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ini ana mantu yang satu ni,<bt>This one daughter-in-law here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lebe bae kasi sang lu dari tuju ana laki-laki!&gt;&gt;<bt>is better for you than seven sons!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meshiv (shwv hif): one who brings"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">meshiv (shwv hif): one who brings back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khalkel (kwl piʕel): one who supplies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">khalkel (kwl piʕel): one who supplies</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔet-seyvatekh: your gray-headedness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">ʔet-seyvatekh: your gray-headedness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kallatekh: your daughter-in-law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">kallatekh: your daughter-in-law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tovah lakh: better fo you. It"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">tovah lakh: better fo you. It shows Ruthʔs cheSed very clearly. This would not be said at most baby showers. But Ruth has resolved all kinds of problems for Naʕomi.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Na'omi paló ame sang itu ana, ju piara bae-bae sama ke dia pung ana sandiri.<bt>Na'omi embraced that child, and raised/cared for him well as if he were her own child. [EXEG: Hubbard, BART, TN, on ‘breast’ and ‘nurse’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatshitehu: she put him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vatshitehu: she put him</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəcheqahh: in her lap - might"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">bəcheqahh: in her lap - might mean that she hanaied him as far as the family was concerned. CHECK. Jacob formally adopted Josephʔs sons, and this changed the tribal structure and territorial rights; Levi had no territory, but Josephʔs two sons did.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vathi-lo lʔomenet: she was just like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">vathi-lo lʔomenet: she was just like a nurse or a nanny to him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais parampuan di itu kota dong omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Sakarang su sama ke Na'omi su dapa ana ulang lai! Talalu hebat, é!&gt;&gt; Ju dong kasi nama sang dia &lt;Obed&gt;.<bt>So the women in that city spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Awii! [+amazement] Now it is as if Na'omi has had a child again! That's so great, é!&gt;&gt; And they named him &lt;Obed&gt;. [DISCOURSE: reflecting/reinforcing speaker attitude.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu Obed bésar datang, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Isai. Isai dapa satu ana, nama Daud, yang jadi raja.<bt>When Obed grew up, he had a son named Isai. Isai had a child named Daud, who became raja.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəkhenot: the neighbor ladies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">shəkhenot: the neighbor ladies</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ini ni, dong pung moyang Peres pung turunan:<bt>This here is their ancestor Peres' descendants:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Peres barana sang Hesron.<bt>Peres gave birth to Hesron. [DISCOURSE: following descending genealogy style and phrasing tested in Matthew. Yes, in genealogies, males can ‘give birth to, beget = become a genealogical forefather to’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="howliyd (yld hif): cause to bear,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2013-09-22 10:38:04Z" status="Information">howliyd (yld hif): cause to bear, father. TWOT: likely that the different forms mean different things. In most every instance actual paternity is represented by the Hiphil and a more general relationship like relationship of peoples (the Table of Nations, Gen 10) uses the Qal... The word does not necessarily point to the generation immediately following. In Hebrew thought, an individual by the act of giving birth to a child becomes a parent or ancestor of all who will be descended from this child. Just as Christ is called a son of David and a son of Abraham, ya4lad may show the beginning of an individualʔs relationship to any descendant. JG: Nine generations, based on probable ages of childbearing, is between 180 and 325 years, more or less, and from the Patriarchs to David is like 700 years. So there must have been some generation skipping in the genealogies here as elsewhere. Even a 40-year calculation would account for only half the time. And Nakshon, the middle one, was Aaronʔs brother-in-law, which foreshortens the whole thing. IVP: It is sometimes held that a period of 40 years, the duration, for instance, of the wilderness wanderings, is to be taken as a round *number indicating a generation... That some genealogies in the Bible omit some generations is demonstrable (compare Mt. 1:1 with 1:2-17). For instance, the list of Aaronʔs descendants in Ezr. 7:1-5 omits six names which are given in 1 Ch. 6:3-14. (See also *Chronology Of The Old Testament, III. a.) This is readily understandable from the formulae, for the word "ben" could mean not only son but also ʔgrandsonʔ and ʔdescendantʔ, and in like manner it is probable that the verb "yalad" could mean not only ʔbearʔ in the immediate physical sense but also ʔbecome the ancestor ofʔ (the noun yeled from this verb has the meaning of descendant in Is. 29:23)... although Moses is apparently in the fourth generation from the Patriarch Jacob through Levi, Kohath and Amram (Ex. 6:20; 1 Ch. 6:1-3), yet Mosesʔ contemporary Bezalel is in the seventh generation from Jacob through Judah, Perez, Hezron, Caleb, Hur and Uri (1 Ch. 2:18-20), and his younger contemporary Joshua is in the twelfth generation from Jacob through Joseph, Ephraim, Beriah, Rephah, Resheph, Telah, Tahan, Laadan, Ammihud, Elishama and Nun (1 Ch. 7:23-27). Hence there is a possibility that Mosesʔ genealogy is abbreviated by comparison with those of Joshua and even Bezalel. Secondly, Mosesʔ ‘father’ Amram and his brothers gave rise to the clans of Amramites, Izharites, etc., who already numbered 8,600 male members alone within a year of the Exodus (Nu. 3:27-28), an unlikely situation unless Amram and his brothers themselves flourished distinctly earlier than Moses. Thirdly, the wording that by Amram Jochebed ‘bore’ Moses, Aaron and Miriam (Ex. 6:20; Nu. 26:59), like ‘became the father’, AV ‘begat’, in Gn. 5 and 11, need not imply immediate parenthood but also simply descent.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="19" />Hesron barana sang Ram.<bt>Hesron gave birth to Ram.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ram barana sang Aminadab.<bt>Ram gave birth to Aminadab.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="20" />Aminadab barana sang Nahason.<bt>Aminadab gave birth to Nahason.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nahason barana sang Salmon.<bt>Nahason gave birth to Salmon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="21" />Salmon barana sang Bo'as.<bt>Salmon gave birth to Bo'as.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bo'as barana sang Obed.<bt>Bo'as gave birth to Obed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="22" />Obed barana sang Isai.<bt>Obed gave birth to Isai.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Isai barana sang raja Daud.<bt>Isai gave birth to raja Daud.</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>